<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan-King     04-11 0845</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-King,0874</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memories Of The Past, New Hope, For Once And Future King</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a padlocked shed near the old royal palace, the limousine of the last Afghan king waits in the dust. The black Daimler's tires are flat, but the silver royal crest on the door is untarnished. The car is an apt symbol for <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON>, the 74-year-old exile whose return is talked about by Afghans across the political spectrum as a way of ending the decade-old civil war between an authoritarian government and Moslem fundamentalists. Sixteen years after he was deposed, the ex-king remains a symbol of better days _ of a time when Afghans were not slaughtering each other in horrific numbers. The problem is finding a way for him to return. `` The car is ready for him. It would be good if he came back,'' said a man who knew the whereabouts of <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Daimler </ORGANIZATION>. Then, looking around even though no one else was within hearing distance, the slender university graduate added: `` Please do n't write my name. Others are less fearful. `` If King <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> wants to work for his country, he can have a positive role in bringing peace,'' said <PERSON> Wadir </PERSON> <PERSON> Safi </PERSON>, dean of law and political science at <ORGANIZATION> Kabul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` Even if he did n't do much for the progress of our country, he did n't kill anybody,'' said <PERSON> Safi </PERSON>, who studied at <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Charles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> About a month ago, <PERSON> Safi </PERSON>'s views were published in a new weekly newspaper, the Akbar-e-Hafta. The article was accompanied by the first photograph of the former king that <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> residents can remember seeing published in the government-supervised media since <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> was overthrown in 1973. The issue quickly sold out, although its price of 20 cents is four or five times that of other newspapers. Even illiterate people scrambled for copies. `` All the people like <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON>,'' a shopkeeper said on condition of anonymity. `` In <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON>'s time there was not killing of people,'' the father of 10 added. Even President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, a former secret police chief, has said talks with the ex-king could be useful. In mid-February, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said he had sent emissaries to <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON>'s exile home in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. A spokesman for the aging ex-monarch promptly denied any contacts with <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s Soviet-style regime. U.S.-backed Moslem fundamentalist guerrillas, operating from headquarters across the border in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, are divided about reinstating the monarchy. Any future role in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> for <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> has been rejected by hard-liners among the rebels, such as <PERSON> Rasul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayyaf </PERSON>, leader of one of the seven parties in the Pakistan-based guerrilla alliance. Some moderate leaders, such as <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Gailani </PERSON> who once served as the king's religious adviser, say they would accept his return as a constitutional monarch, a sort of living flag to help unite the Afghan people. The king himself seems amenable. In early February, as the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was withdrawing its last soldiers from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and ending nine years of combat support for the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government, <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> said: `` I am prepared to render without any claim or precondition any service to my country which would reflect the will of the majority of my compatriots.'' The sticky question is how to reconcile the poles-apart politics of <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION>, the rebels' Islamic fundamentalism and a monarchy The rebels refuse to deal with the party, whose communist beginnings never took root among the fervently capitalist Afghans. The party, whose leadership changes have come only through coup, assassination or purge, says it is willing to `` share'' power but will never step aside completely. In four decades on the throne, <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> himself proved a less than dynamic leader. He was only 19 in 1933 when he became king upon the assassination of his father, <PERSON> Nadir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON>. For the next 20 years his uncles ran the country. In 1953, his cousin, <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Daoud </PERSON>, became prime minister and tried to push a feudalistic, tribal nation toward the 20th century by such means as freeing women of their all-enveloping robes. In 1963, <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> finally exerted himself. <PERSON> Daoud </PERSON> resigned, waited a decade, and overthrew his cousin the king. Five years later, in 1978, <PERSON> Daoud </PERSON> was assassinated in a coup that brought the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> to power with a succession of leaders. Since then about 1 million Afghans have been killed in the war. Another 5 million have fled to neighboring <LOCATION> Paistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, leaving <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> with a population of 10 million. Throughout the war, <PERSON> Zahir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Daimler </ORGANIZATION>, a car that is somehow sleek and bulky at the same time, has been unscathed. Periodically it is dusted by a man with only childhood memories of the monarchy, a man who does not want to give his name and hopes the car remains safe until the king returns. The Daimler waits, along with five other royal automobiles, in a simple white-washed structure behind the national museum, abou 300 yards from the early 20th century Darulaman Palace which now houses the defense ministry.
</TEXT>
