<HEAD>Fire, Explosion At Chevron Plant; 6 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire erupted Monday at a <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> oil refinery plant, injuring at least seven workers and sending 100-foot flames shooting into the sky. The fire apparently started at 12:46 p.m. when an explosion shook a 100-foot-tall column in a refinery processing plant where gasoline is manufactured, said <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. Thick black smoke and flames rose into the sky as about 40 firefighters from <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> and the city of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> battled the blaze, which was declared under control about four hours later, <PERSON> Holt </PERSON> said. `` The fire is still burning and we have not been able to get in to assess the cause or the totality of damage,'' said <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>, who refused to estimate a damage amount. Three Chevron operators were flown to <LOCATION> Brookside </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pablo </LOCATION> where a hospital spokesman said they were in stable condition with second degree burns. One man suffered burns over 70 percent of his body and the other two had burns over 20 percent to 30 percent of their bodies. Another Chevron operator was taken to <LOCATION> Doctor </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Pinole </LOCATION>, where he was reported in stable condition after being treated for smoke inhalation, according to the nursing supervisor. <ORGANIZATION> Alta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> reported that one <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> fire marshal was admitted with second degree burns on his face, ears and neck and was having respiratory difficulties, said hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>. At least two other people were reported injured but there was no immediate word on the extent of their injuries. The facility is <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s second largest refinery on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and produces about 265,000 barrels of crude oil daily.
