<HEAD>State Department Reverses Itself, OKs Coast Guard Band's Soviet Appearance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a policy reversal, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to let the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Band </ORGANIZATION> perform this June at a <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> concert commemorating last year's U.S.-Soviet arms treaty. Earlier this year, the <ORGANIZATION> Leningrad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> invited the Connecticut-based military band to play with the <ORGANIZATION> Leningrad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Band </ORGANIZATION> in a joint concert June 22 in honor of the first anniversary of the treaty banning intermediate-range nuclear missiles. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embraced the idea, according to Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., but higher-level officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> rejected it without explanation <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> and officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, protested the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> decision to scuttle the trip. In a letter last month to <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON>, the department's legislative liaison, <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> said he could not understand `` what reason could possibly exist for refusing this gracious and generous invitation during this period of excellent relations. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> told <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> on Monday that the trip was back on. `` The band shows the best of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' the congressman said. `` The <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> people will love it.'' One source said <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials feared the trip would interfere with a concurrent visit by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military officials and were uneasy about the idea of having an American military unit performing in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> said he believes the reluctance stems from the problems Americans have with responding to glasnost, the Soviets' new policy of openness `` It's just symbolic of the difficulty of the new opportunities in the relationship with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Even the simplest and smallest symbol that they're willing to try ... was a major hurdle to get across,'' <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials for Soviet affairs could not be reached for comment following <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>'s announcement, which came late Monday afternoon <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> officials are paying for the band's hotel, meals and local transportation, <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has to supply air travel to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
