<HEAD>Kemp Plans Effort to Evict Drug Dealers from Public Housing Projects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Housing and Urban Development Secretary <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> says his proposals to get drugs out of <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> housing projects can be followed in the rest of the nation, too. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> on Monday proposed actions against drugs in the federally supported housing projects of the nation's capital, including more police patrols, installing security fences and guarded entrances, and requiring photo identification cards for residents. He announced the moves as part of the federal government's drug crackdown in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, but said the proposals `` are appropriate and will be suggested'' to every public housing authority in the nation. `` I'm asking today the <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> police chief and the public housing authority of <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, along with public housing authorities around the country, to engage in those type of operations that can clear out and secure public housing projects from drug users and abusers and dealers,'' <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said. In the nation's capital, <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said he would waive <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> grievance hearing requirements that can delay evictions from public housing for months. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> took steps recently to remove those requirements in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> outlined his plan at a news conference where national drug policy director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> and Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> announced a major new effort to combat drugs in the nation's capital. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said local police and public housing authorities should issue photo identification cards to residents of federally supported housing projects so that legitimate residents can be distinguished from outsiders. He said security guards would be trained and `` a better presence of public housing and city police'' would be provided. A part of the effort would be a general cleanup of projects, including removal of graffiti. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> acknowledged that many of the steps are things <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> should be doing anyway, and said many of the proposals were based on successful tests by local housing authorities at projects in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> and elsewhere. He said he would finance the anti-drug effort with existing money appropriated for public housing rehabilitation and operating subsidies. He put no price tag on the effort. `` If it's not enough, I'll ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for a supplemental'' appropriation, he said. <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assisted </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the city's public housing projects, said city housing officials were discussing <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s proposal and had no immediate response. But she said the district is already issuing photo cards to residents of high-rise projects for senior citizens. Most units for other residents are apartments or town houses, she said, and use of the cards is `` a much different issue'' for families. She said the district already has asked <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> for more money to pay for 100 additional housing guards and for more security fences. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> also will: _ Ask <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys to seize the apartments of drug dealers and return them to the public housing authorities _ Seek ways to terminate federal housing subsidies, such as <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> vouchers and housing certificates, for anyone convicted of using or selling drugs _ Attempt to reclaim vacant units sometimes used by drug dealers and abusers, and enforce housing codes and standards _ Encourage resident management of public housing projects _ Establish an anti-drug hotline to encourage residents to make confidential reports on drug-related crimes _ Encourage youth sports leagues in the projects to steer youngsters away from drugs
