<FIRST>r w PM-Lead-Schools     04-11 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lead-Schools,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lead Found in Same Model Water Coolers Used by Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lead-Tanks List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Water fountains with excessive levels of lead because of tanks lined with the toxic metal are being used at elementary and secondary schools, and more than 100 models have unhealthy levels, the government says. The exact number of coolers with the lead-lined tanks is not known, but the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> did say that more than a million other coolers are in use that have lead soldering or lead in some other form. Although the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> lacks the authority to order lead testing in schools, a law enacted last year requires states to begin a program to assist school districts in testing for lead in drinking water. Many such programs are under way. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials also said Monday they would soon issue a detailed guide for school officials on how to testfor unhealthy lead levels, and the agency listed more than 100 manufacturers' model numbers for fountains in which lead levels were found to be of concern. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it discovered the lead-lined tanks while inspecting 22 coolers provided by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. The nine with lead-lined tanks were all models like those used in schools. Those coolers, all made by <ORGANIZATION> Halsey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, mostly had lead levels of more than several hundred parts per billion, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. In some cases, when long-standing water was tested, the level was more than 1,000 parts per billion, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> considers a lead level of 20 parts per billion in water to pose health risks especially if a child is exposed to lead poisoning from other sources as well. Lead is a toxic metal that is harmful to health even at low levels of exposure and poses increased risks to children. It can cause damage to the brain and nervous system and lead to learning disabilities, hearing impairment, and interference in the formation of red blood cells, according to the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>. `` There are a few hundred thousand children who have enough lead from other sources so when lead from drinking water is added at levels of 20 parts per billion there will be some adverse health impact,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> water contamination office, in an interview. The agency also said that three major manufacturers of school water coolers have acknowleged that more than a million coolers have some lead components _ usually lead soldering at joints. Two other companies did not reply to the inquiries and another said it manufactured no coolers with lead soldering. The agency gave no specific levels of lead in water from all the coolers cited by model numbers, but said the coolers were singled out only after levels were found to be in the unhealthy range. After the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> issues a final list of coolers with lead-lined tanks later this year, the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> intends to seek their recall by the manufacturer, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmeltzer </PERSON>, director of compliance at the commission. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials said that school water fountains likely account for only a `` very small'' part of the lead exposure that faces youngsters. In some cases it's uncertain whether the high lead levels in some model coolers was from the coolers or water pipes that feed the coolers. In addition to the nine lead-lined coolers from the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> received two additional coolers with lead-lined tanks from school officials in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said. The law that was passed last year also requires the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to issued detailed guidelines on how to detect lead contamination in school water systems and sets a timetable for replacing or fixing coolers that pose a health hazard because of lead contamination. The coolers cited by model number were manufactured by three companies _ <ORGANIZATION> Halsey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taylor </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> EBCO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Sunroc </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said two other companies have yet to reply to inquiries on lead content in their coolers and a third said it produced no coolers with lead components.
</TEXT>
