<UNK>Bush Signs Whistleblower Protection Bill</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> signed a bill to protect federal whistleblowers who report government waste and fraud, calling it a `` significant improvement'' over a version vetoed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The bill signed by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Monday gives more job protection to federal employees who disclose misdeeds and mismanagement in their agencies. `` The true whistleblower is a public servant of the highest order,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said at a bill-signing ceremony in the Old Executive Office Building attended by the measure's congressional sponsors. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> vetoed a similar measure last fall. Stripped from the new version _ which was approved unanimously in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and by a voice vote in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> _ is a provision opposed by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> that would have permitted the Office of Special Counsel to go to court on behalf of whistleblowers. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> protested this would have resulted in federal agencies fighting court battles against each other. The new version `` addresses the chief constitutional concerns raised by earlier versions of this legislation,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` The bill I am signing today is a significant improvement over legislation enacted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year.'' Under the new act, employees fighting for their jobs would face less stringent standards of proof that their firing or demotion came as the result of whistleblowing. The Office of the Special Counsel, established eight years ago to investigate civil service abuses, would become an independent agency.
