<FIRST>r w PM-FuelEconomy     04-11 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fuel Economy,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Car Average Mileage of 33 mpg Possible by 1995, Congress Told</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cars could average 33 miles per gallon by 1995, but automakers are unlikely to make the necessary engineering changes on their own, the congressional <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION> says. The higher average, about 5 mpg above the present one for new cars, could be reached if automakers began immediately to move available fuel-conservation technology into their cars at a more rapid pace, an analyst with the office told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on Monday. Those changes include better tires, more aerodynamic body design and engine improvements, said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON>, senior associate with the office. `` We calculate that this level of efficiency could be obtained without a performance loss or the need to move to smaller vehicles, at a cost that would be compensated for by fuel savings,'' <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> told the oversight and investigations subcommttee, chaired by Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich. But the office `` doubts that the industry will pursue this course without a further economic or regulatory incentive to do so,'' <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> have said high fuel-economy standards are difficult to reach because of the public's demand for larger, high-powered cars. The OTA analysis struck a middle course between the positions of advocates of tighter fuel-economy standards and the major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers. Energy conservation groups have proposed a 45 mpg fuel-economy goal for cars by 2000, a level <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> said was `` virtually impossible'' to reach. Neither <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> nor <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> could provide estimates of attainable fuel efficiency for 1995. `` We have n't gone out that far in our prognostications, largely because there are just too many variables to deal with, the largest of which is fuel cost,'' said <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON>. The office's analysis assumed a $ 1.10 per gallon price for gasoline, <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> said. The corporate average fuel economy standard requires the mix of 1989 cars sold by each automaker to average 26.5 mpg or better. The average fuel-efficiency for all new passenger cars in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1987 was 28 mpg and <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> said the present level is about the same. Among the presently available technologies whose adoption could improve fuel efficiency are more aerodynamic styling, improved tire composition and design and improved pumps and other components, <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> said. Greater use of front-wheel drive, four-speed automatic shift, four-cylinder and four-valve engines and low-friction rings and pistons would also help increase the average fuel efficiency of cars in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> said. The goal likely could n't be reached if present trends toward greater performance and luxury continued, or if the industry had to comply with stricter pollution-control standards that required technologies that reduce fuel efficiency, <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> said.
