<SECOND>PM-Social Security,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chaos Overwhelms Special Line to Social Security Office, Witnesses
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People who called an expanded toll-free telephone service offered by the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> met with busy signals, endless waits on hold and misinformation when they did get through, witnesses told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel. <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, told the the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging that she was put on hold three times for 20 minutes, then told she would have to wait 30 days for the answer to a question on moving her mother's checks into a new account. A phone representative neglected to tell <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Lippert </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> that she needed to file a claim to get a widow's benefit, and she said it took five months to wade through red tape before the problem was solved `` I would like to point out that for the past five months, I have only received my own Social Security check, which is $ 70 less than my rent alone,'' she told the panel on Monday. The administration began the 800-number service last October, hoping to improve convenience and accessibility to the public by making phone representatives available for 12 hours per day, instead of eight. The system, in which calls to local Social Security offices are routed to any of 37 national `` teleservice'' centers, has been implemented so far in 60 percent of the nation and received 22 million calls. The service was touted in two mailings to a total of 36 million beneficiaries in December and February. Lawmakers began hearing about the system after national busy signal rates reached 43 percent in January, followed by 35 percent in February. The rate dipped to 9 percent in March, but only after calls dropped from 4.8 million in March to 3.4 million in February, and after <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> brought in staff members in from other offices to answer calls, a <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> official testified. `` While the reassignment of staff contributed to the reduction of this busy signal rate for March, it raises questions about the impact on the operations of the field facilities,'' <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Delfico </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>'s Human Resources Division said in a prepared statement. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sturdivant </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, told the panel that <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Dorcas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> `` has created sweatshop conditions for teleservice employees.'' `` She is pressuring employees to complete calls in an average of 200 seconds,'' he said, adding that the employees are being denied sick leave. <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> said it reduced the busy signal rate in March partly through the use of a system to reroute calls during peak calling times. `` As we have identified problems and gained experience with the system, we have been able to modify our procedures along the way in order to improve our performance,'' <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> told the panel. `` This will be the largest 800-number in the world,'' she said in a prepared text. `` I want it to be the best.'' A survey conducted by <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> in February found that 84 percent of callers interviewed were satisfied with the phone service and 98 percent thought they had been treated courteously, the administration said. <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> said the latest survey placed the system-wide accuracy rate at 94 percent. But <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Delfico </PERSON> said that an <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> study last December found that the number of incorrect 800-number responses ranged from 2.5 percent for a question on disability benefits to 22.9 percent for a question on the annual earnings test for people 70 years old and over. The service handled 22 million calls during its first six months.
