<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It lacked the proper equipment and dawdled when it should have been racing against the clock, but the oil-smeared `` response team'' promised to revise its contingency plan and do better next time. The Allyeska-Exxxon Response Team was the last of the 103 teams to cross the finish line in the 14th-annual Ski-to-Sea Relay near <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION>. `` We were well-prepared. We had a good plan. But, darn, the thing just was n't adequate,'' team member <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Nordlund </PERSON> said Monday. <PERSON> Nordlund </PERSON> said his team was neither sanctioned nor supported by <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> nor <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the companies blamed for the slow response to the Valdez oil spill. It was just coincidence that team members had crude oil on their faces and clothes, he said. In fact, all but one of the team members work for the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, which is no stranger to oil companies. Each team included a downhill skier, who began the relay at the top of the <ORGANIZATION> Eaglecrest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ski </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> and passed the baton to a cross-country skier, two runners and a bicyclist. <PERSON> Nordlund </PERSON>, a legislative aide, noted his bicycle was not designed for the job. `` We thought it was a state-of-the-art bike. It actually was a little small. It was n't large enough to deal with the size of the race,'' he said. `` Well, it basically was a little kid's bike.'' The downhill skier in <PERSON> Nordlund </PERSON>'s team missed all the gates, `` and unfortunately there's a penalty each time you do that,'' he said. `` I think she skied part of the way backwards.'' Things got worse when the team's cross-country skier took over. `` He's our lawyer and he was dressed up in a suit and tie, smoking a cigar,'' <PERSON> Nordlund </PERSON> recalled. `` After the start he realized his cigar went out so he stopped and took the time to light it. `` He figured there just was n't much of a hurry. Things were under control. He had The Wall Street Journal with him and he read that.'' <PERSON> Wendie </PERSON> <PERSON> Marriott </PERSON>, who organized the weekend race as the city's recreation supervisor, said she heard that the team's runners actually ran _ backward `` The team was purposely trying to come in last, which it did,'' she observed. `` The idea was to clean up the mess at the end of the race.'' <PERSON> Nordlund </PERSON> said the team learned a lot from the experience. `` We'll do it better next time,'' he said. `` You can trust us.''
