<HEAD>Audit: Military Stuck with Millions Worth of Useless Parts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The military has a multimillion-dollar stockpile of useless spare parts because contractors fail to follow specifications and the government neglects to check the shipments, a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> auditor told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. A two-year audit conducted at the <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Robins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> concluded an estimated $ 104 million worth of parts failed to conform `` to essential or critical operational characteristics,'' according to a report released Monday to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The report detailed problems both with the way government contractors ship out parts and the way the military accepts and pays for parts without making sure they meet rigidly drawn specifications. `` Obviously we have a lot of material out there that is not combat-ready,'' Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, told a hearing of the committee, which he chairs. `` I want to know why we are accepting substandard parts.'' Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> told <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> he would order spot inspections of parts as they're delivered. And Brig. Gen. <PERSON> M.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepe </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> told <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> has started to equip its depots with equipment to test parts as they come in. `` It's obvious we need to do more checking,'' <PERSON> Pepe </PERSON> said. `` We had n't been doing enough checking.'' In addition, since July 1988 competitive contracts have included a one-year warranty requiring replacement or refund of substandard parts, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Vander </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaaf </PERSON>, deputy inspector general for the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said the audit covered spare parts chosen randomly from the <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Robins </ORGANIZATION> warehouse. About 58 percent, or $ 12.9 millon worth, of the gun parts tested in the study were unusable. Only 8 percent of examined gun parts, with such functions as feeding ammunition into 20mm and 30mm aircraft-mounted guns, conformed to specifications, the audit report said. Tests of mounted bearings, which are used in aircraft landing gears and wing flaps and on helicopter main rotor heads, indicated 38 percent conformed to specifications and 30 percent were unusable. Below-standard parts routinely were accepted and used, though the failure to conform to specifications meant they did n't last as long as they would have if they met the standards, the report said. <PERSON> Vander </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaaf </PERSON> said auditors found numerous examples of contractors who shipped defective parts to one branch of the service, but other branches were n't told of the problems and gave the same contractor orders for identical or similar parts. In one case, `` one part of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> gave new work to a contractor while another part of the same <ORGANIZATION> Logistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> hauled $ 1.5 million worth of the same contractor's parts to the scrap yard,'' <PERSON> Vander </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaaf </PERSON> testified.
