<NOTE>Coast Guard to Ease Seizure Rules in Drug Cases</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> is making permanent its decision not to seize vessels when only small quantities of drugs are found on board. The agency announced Monday a rulemaking that would subject the owners of commercial fishing vessels to a summons in cases when personal-use quantities of illegal drugs are found on their ships. The issuing of summonses in such cases was instituted on an interim basis Feb. 16 and the rulemaking would make that permanent, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said. Before that, vessels had been subject to immediate seizure when any quantity of drugs was found. The new regulation covers commercial fishing, fish processing and fish tender vessels. Separate laws extend similar protection to ferry boats, cruise ships and other commercial vessels in cases in which a passenger brings small quantities of drugs on board. However, these vessels remain subject to seizure if there is evidence that the master or operator of the vessel was aware of the violation.
