<HEAD>Evacuations Ordered Over Fear of Toxic Smoke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENTURA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire at a chemical plant sent smoke billowing over a community east of here on Monday night, prompting most of the town's evacuation, authorities said. There were unconfirmed reports that up to 35 people, including one firefighter, suffered ill effects from the smoke, said <LOCATION> Ventura </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's Sgt. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Backman </PERSON>. `` The deputies out there tell me you do n't have to be out there too long before you feel the pressure in your chest,'' he said. About 200 residents of Saticoy were evacuated from the northeast portion of the unincorporated town a few hours after the blaze began, but that was later expanded to include most of the town, <PERSON> Backman </PERSON> said. The blaze erupted around 6 p.m. in a small chemical plant called Pacific Intermediaries and continued burning five hours later. It was not immediately known what chemical was involved. `` It's a hazardous material that's water-reactant, which means they ca n't use water to put it out, but they're about to dump about 50 tons of sand on it,'' a <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> dispatcher said late Monday night. A half-mile section of busy Highway 118 was shut down as a precaution because of the smoke, and was expected to remain closed through the night, the dispatcher said. Ventura is 75 miles northwest of downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>.
