<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar marginally rose against the Japanese yen Tuesday, while share prices sharply rebounded on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar closed at 132.62 yen, down 0.09 yen from Monday's close of 132.53 yen The currency opened at 132.87 yen and fluctuated within a range of 132.60-132 .89 yen The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost 186.03 points Monday, recouped 250.56 points, or 0.76 percent, to finish trading at 33,249.58. Dealers said the index started lower amid political uncertainties prior to parliamentary testimony by Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> Tuesday morning about receiving political donations from the firm at the center of a major stock-profiteering and bribery scandal. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said he had received about $ 1 million from the firm. He denied taking bribes and continued to fend off opposition calls for his resignation. Investors were reassured as <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said nothing new, a dealer at a major securities firm said on condition of anonymity. Opposition parties have stalemated parliamentary proceedings, demanding a full accounting of governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> politicians' involvement in the scandal surrounding information services conglomerate Recruit Co.. On the foreign exchange, participants mainly adjusted their dollar positions due to a lack of market-affecting incentives, said a trader at the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity Currency traders reacted to <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s statements by buying yen, pushing the dollar slightly lower, he said. `` The yen edged up as some investors got relieved and bought the currency because <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> did n't say anything shocking before the Parliament this morning,'' he said.
