<HEAD>Haitians Face Air Piracy Charges In Hijack of Missionary Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Duer, Cap Haitien cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Haitian soldiers who fired their way aboard a small plane before hijacking it to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> were being questioned about their role in a recent failed coup attempt in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, authorities and witnesses said. The plane was carrying eight people, including three American missionaries, when the Fort Lauderdale-bound flight was hijacked Monday. No one was injured. Passengers said the soldiers did not threaten them and had hoped to talk to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The two were to be arraigned this afternoon on air piracy charges charges, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. Witnesses said the pair ran out waving guns and shooting in the air Monday on the tarmac at Cap Haitien airport on <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s northern coast, and forced their way onto the twin-engine <ORGANIZATION> Cessna </ORGANIZATION> 402. They threw down their weapons and surrendered upon arrival at <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said. `` These guys were pretty upset,'' said pilot <PERSON> Duer </PERSON> <PERSON> Smedley </PERSON>. `` They were desperate to get out of <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>. They're not like terrorists from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. They are not looking to hurt anyone. They are just looking for a way out of the country.'' <PERSON> Guillaume </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlioze </PERSON>, 25, and <PERSON> Fadael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milord </PERSON>, 29, both of the Haitian capital <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION>, were armed with a .38 - caliber revolver, an assault rifle and a 40mm anti-tank shell, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> They were questioned by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and transferred to the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said investigators were n't certain of the motive behind the hijacking, but, `` there are indications that they are against the government.'' Police sources at Cap Haitien, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the hijackers had deserted from the Dessalines Battalion. The battalion, with 750 soldiers, is one of two military units that tried to bring down Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Prosper </PERSON> <PERSON> Avril </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s military president, on April 2. By Monday, <PERSON> Avril </PERSON>'s loyal 1,100-member Presidential Guard appeared to have quieted rebellious outbreaks. <PERSON> Smedley </PERSON> said the pair told him they wanted to talk to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> after they surrendered. `` I asked him where he wanted to go and he said ` <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, I have a lot of things to tell <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>,''' the pilot said. `` The military has been fighting down there for the last week,'' <PERSON> Smedley </PERSON> said. `` I think these guys were just on the losing side. I got the impression that they thought if they stayed in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, they would be killed.'' Passenger <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Keyser </PERSON>, a missionary from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barrington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, said the hijack was frightening at first. `` They scared us,'' <PERSON> Keyser </PERSON> said. `` But they were basically harmless. They actually expected President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to be waiting for them outside the plane.'' `` They were more scared then we were,'' said another missionary, <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kato </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kato </PERSON>, <PERSON> Keyser </PERSON> and the other missionary aboard, <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON>, also of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barrington </LOCATION>, are members of the Missionary Aviation Fellowship of <LOCATION> Redlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. Four Haitians also were on the flight, said fellowship spokeswoman <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> The Christian fellowship was founded in 1945 and operates 145 aircraft, primarily to fly doctors, medical supplies and missionaries to Third World countries. In October 1987, a fellowship single-engine plane was hijacked in <LOCATION> Suriname </LOCATION>. The pilot was held by a rebel guerrilla group before being released unharmed.
