<HEAD>Lebanon Hostage Came Within Minutes Of Being Released, Sister Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Teacher <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON>, who marked his third anniversary as a hostage in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> today, came within 10 minutes of being released in January before something mysteriously went wrong, said his sister, <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Spence </PERSON>. `` Our hopes were highest in January and we now know that <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> was 10 minutes away from being released,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> said in a <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> radio interview. `` He was clean shaven. He had fresh clothes. His hair was cut and he was ready for release.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> said that she and her sister <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillham </PERSON> were wating patiently at a hotel in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> with a plane standing by to fly them to <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> as soon as they received word their brother was free. `` Then suddenly, within a split second, our hopes died,'' she said. `` We do n't know what went wrong and we still do n't know what happened.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> did not indicate the source of the family's information <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON>, 38, disappeared while walking to work at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beirut </ORGANIZATION> on April 11, 1986. No one has claimed responsibility for holding him. The <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> man has dual British and Irish citizenship. Mrs. <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> also said she was bitter that the controversy over author <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> may have hampered efforts to release her brother. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> broke diplomatic ties in February after <LOCATION> Iranian </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> called for the murder of <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, a British citizen, for his novel `` The Satanic Verses.'' Many Moslems consider the book blasphemous. `` With the like of the <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> case, yes, I did get very bitter with him,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> was a Moslem, a person of the Moslem faith. There was my brother. His life was held against <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Gillham </PERSON> said: `` It has been a very, very hard three years. We have had no life whatsoever because our whole life revolves around <PERSON> Brian </PERSON>. We keep thinking of him, even in our sleep. `` We dream about <PERSON> Brian </PERSON>, about the people holding him, what they are fighting about and hope someday he'll come back to us.'' <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON> is one of 15 foreigners, nine of them Americans, missing in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The longest-held is <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. He was kidnapped on March 16, 1985. On Monday, <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrell </PERSON>, girlfriend of missing British journalist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, met Foreign Secretary Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>, but said she was `` disappointed'' in the government's strategy to secure the hostages' release.
