<HEAD>Quake Hits Kuril Islands In Soviet Far East</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A strong earthquake shook the sparsely populated <LOCATION> Kuril </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> today and was felt on the <LOCATION> Kamchatka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, Soviet officials said. There were no reports of injury or damage. The earthquake registered 6.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale and was centered in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> about 100 miles southeast of the southern tip of the peninsula, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tsumani </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. It occurred at 7:58 a.m. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> time and registered between 7-8 points on the 12-point Soviet scale, said <PERSON> Yulia </PERSON> <PERSON> Krasnopeeva </PERSON>, an official at the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seismological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. That classified it as a `` very strong'' or `` destructive'' on the Soviet scale, which is based on visible physical effects. Ms. <PERSON> Krasnopeeva </PERSON> said the quake registered 4 on the Soviet scale in the city of <LOCATION> Petropavlovsk </LOCATION> about 310 miles to the north on the <LOCATION> Kamchatka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. `` There were no injuries or damage,'' the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said in a brief report. There was no threat of a destructive Pacific-wide tsunami, or tidal wave, the warning center said. The <LOCATION> Kamchatka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> extends about 750 miles south from the Soviet mainland and divides the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> from the Sea of <LOCATION> Okhotsk </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude. An earthquake of registering 6 on the scale can cause severe damage. A 7 reading is a `` major'' earthquake, capable of widespread damage.
