<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The container holding heavy water and an electrode resembled a high school chemistry experiment. Only the beeps of a neutron counter showed that nuclear fusion might really be happening at room temperature. `` There's no question it's fusion,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Livesay </PERSON>, a metallurgist who worked on the project at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> here. `` I still do n't believe it, even though I see it.'' Researchers at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> and at <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, on Monday announced the results of separate experiments that they said appeared to confirm a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> experiment that aroused tremendous skepticism when it was announced last month. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahaffey </PERSON>, a senior researcher at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION>, said the school's experiment began detecting the release of subatomic neutron particles last weekend, a sure sign of fusion. `` It's open season on fusion,'' <PERSON> Mahaffey </PERSON> said. <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON>, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> chemistry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION>, said he was elated and relieved by the announcements. He and a colleague, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southampton </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, sent scientists around the world scrambling with their March 23 announcement of a controlled fusion reaction. `` This is just incredible,'' <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` If they indeed have measured the neutron production, that's a real breakthrough. My sincere congratulations to <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION>.'' Nuclear fusion _ the melding together of two atoms with an accompanying release of energy _ normally requires enormously high temperatures. It is the energy source of the sun and hydrogen bombs. Scientists have sought for decades to harness fusion's power because it holds the potential to provide an almost unlimited supply of relatively clean, cheap energy. Unlike nuclear reactors that use fission _ the splitting of atoms _ to derive power, fusion does n't generate significant radioactive waste. In the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> experiment, which was kept behind lead shielding, probes that normally measure 40 neutrons an hour in background radiation were measuring 600 an hour. <PERSON> Mahaffey </PERSON> cautioned that his team had not confirmed whether the process produces more energy than it consumes. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M researchers said their experiment generated a net 1.144 watts of energy in the form of heat. They did n't measure neutrons. The <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> researchers believed the output was the result of fusion but said they were n't ready to rule out the possibility that a chemical reaction was the cause. `` This is a very unusual result, and we have not totally dismissed the possibility of some unusual chemical process which we might have not accounted for and we are currently exploring this possibility further,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, an electro-chemist at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; M. As in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, both the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> researchers used a palladium electrode to pass electric current through heavy water, a form of water that contains a heavy isotope of hydrogen. The <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> researchers said they cut the time needed for the palladium to soak in heavy water by first baking it in a vacuum. `` There is a need for much more money for research in this area if it is going to get the attention it deserves,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>. `` But that's not surprising since this did n't exist two weeks ago.''
