<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Confederate Home for Women, where eight elderly daughters of Civil War soldiers were told they would be taken care of for life, was doomed to close because of dwindling financial support, its chairman said. <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Burhans </PERSON>, president and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Managers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Needy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday she was too embarrassed to say how much money remained in the trust fund that supports the home and women. The women, ages 84 to 98, will be moved to more modern quarters 20 miles outside of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> to make way for the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> Museum of Fine Arts. The two-story building is nestled among the magnolias behind the museum. Once the women are moved, the antiques filling the home will be sold and the museum will move in. The women had signed over their belongings and any future inheritances in exchange for their support at the home. They will lose dozens of worn but valuable antiques in use in the home. In exchange for the home, the state will pay the cost for the women to live at a suburban retirement center. Officials at the home declined requests to interview the residents on Monday. The home _ with its parquet floors, arched doorways, marble fireplace, antique furniture and portraits of Confederate heroes _ was built in 1931 and now needs extensive repairs, Ms. <PERSON> Burhans </PERSON> said. She said replacing the roof cost $ 300,000. The home also needs new plumbing and a new heating system, which would cost four times that amount, she said. `` The state was not going to appropriate the money to repair the home as a residence for eight ladies,'' she said. As many as 79 women once lived there. Not all the board members were in favor of moving the women. `` The museum wants our home,'' said board member <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliff </PERSON>. `` They want it so bad. `` They've been like damn vultures waiting for the ladies to die so they can get it.'' Ms. <PERSON> Oliff </PERSON> said she tried unsuccessfully to persuade other board members to open the home to paying descendants of Confederate soldiers. The board also denied her proposal that a smaller home for the women be opened about eight blocks away. Ms. <PERSON> Burhans </PERSON> said watching the women leave will be hard. They will be taken to see a retirement home this week. `` They are very well-adjusted,'' said <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeJarnette </PERSON>, the home's administrator. The home's board is to meet Thursday to decide where the women will go, Ms. <PERSON> Burhans </PERSON> said.
