public schools did n't develop problems overnight, and neither <PERSON> Laval </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> nor any other superintendent will solve them overnight,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> wrote in the assessment. He said if he kept the job, he would push his <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plan </ORGANIZATION>, which focuses on improving math and reading and giving principals and teachers more latitude. One problem he's faced in the contract negotiations has been his timing. Last fall, for example, he asked for an $ 18,000 housing allowance on top of his $ 95,000 salary. The request came at a time when school budget cuts loomed. After much criticism, he withdrew the allowance proposal. He now is asking for a three-year contract starting at $ 95,000, with future raises linked to what is given to teachers and administrators. Shortly after he was hired, he was granted his request for a $ 15,000 raise.
