<HEAD>Open Letter Asks Bush To Stop Outside Interference in Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some 600 international writers, scientists, religious leaders, academics and artists have signed an open letter asking President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to stop outside interference in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. Signatories ask <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> not to meddle in regional peace efforts and to lift a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade embargo imposed against the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> government four years ago. They suggest <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> talk directly to Nicaraguan officials. `` We believe that good faith must be translated into actions. This is the moment for you to restore direct dialogue with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>,'' says the letter. A Spanish version was released to local and foreign journalists by President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s press office in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. An aide said the letter would be published in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> today. It was signed, among others, by <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> dancer <PERSON> Alicia </PERSON> <PERSON> Alonso </PERSON>, Spanish poet <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Alberti </PERSON>, American actor <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Asner </PERSON>, Italian film director <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertolucci </PERSON>, Brazilian composer <PERSON> Chico </PERSON> <PERSON> Buarque </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Holando </PERSON> and American composer and conductor <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>. Other signatories included actress <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> and authors <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuentes </PERSON>, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON> <PERSON> Grass </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquez </PERSON>. Central American nations should be allowed to `` resolve on their own their own affairs, without any foreign interference,'' the letter said. `` Peace in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> must immediately be re-established.'' To help bring peace, it said, foreign countries must support accords reached by the five <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents Feb. 14 in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. At the February summit, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> promised to institute democratic reforms and hold elections in February 1990, 10 months earlier than planned. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> also freed nearly 2,000 National Guards jailed for almost a decade since the July 1979 triumph of the Sandinista revolution. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> and the presidents of <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> also agreed to produce by mid-May a plan for dismantling the Nicaraguan rebel force known as the Contras. Some 11,000 Contra rebels, along with their families, have been living at border camps in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> since <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> cut off lethal aid to the U.S.-backed guerrillas in February 1988. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> has criticized <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s recently announced proposal for a Contra aid package of up to $ 45 million in humanitarian aid over 10 months. The Nicaraguan leader maintains it would hurt regional peace efforts.
