<HEAD>12 Long-Term `Refuseniks` Permitted to Leave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twelve long-term Jewish `` refuseniks,'' many of whom were denied exit visas on grounds they knew state secrets, have received permission to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on Soviet Jewry. They are the largest single group to be granted visas at one time since the summit meeting between former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> last December in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Included in the list are <PERSON> Aleksandr </PERSON> <PERSON> Piatetsky </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, who has waited 15 years for a visa, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Berenfeld </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, 12 years; and <PERSON> Inna </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorenshrain </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>, 12 years. <PERSON> Shoshana </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON>, chairman of the Soviet Jewry group, said in a statement Monday: `` While we are encouraged by the resolution of the cases of so many long-term refuseniks, we regret that many who seek to emigrate are still denied their right to do so ...'' Emigration from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> last month was the highest since October 1979. Knowledge of sensitive information was given frequently in the past as a reason for denying visas to Jewish scientists or others who had been involved in government work. One of the reforms pledged by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was to ease the restriction.
