<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Voters went to the polls today with Mayor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> so heavily favored for an unprecedented fifth term that turnout was expected to hit an all-time low. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, 71, needed to capture at least 50 percent of the votes against nine opponents to avoid a June 6 runoff for the four-year office. None of the candidates runs on a party line. The only serious challenger, freshman City Councilman <PERSON> Nate </PERSON> <PERSON> Holden </PERSON>, has accused <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> of ignoring his roots and the city's impoverished south side and favoring big business and foreign trade `` He's been in office too long,'' said <PERSON> Holden </PERSON>, who like <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> is black. `` They're not going to vote for him out of habit anymore.'' On Monday, <PERSON> City </PERSON> <PERSON> Clerk </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> predicted turnout of 25 percent to 30 percent _ `` a historical low for a mayoral election.'' Turnout figures were not immediately available this morning. But <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, the son of sharecroppers and grandson of slaves, has managed to escape responsibility for many of the city's problems, including drugs and gangs Even a current investigation of <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> by the city attorney's office for performing consulting work with two banks that do business with the city seemed to have had little effect on the mayor <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> has returned the $ 18,000 fees he was paid and called the charges politically motivated. Pollsters and would-be candidates conclude that <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, a congenial former city police lieutenant and councilman, has managed to be associated with <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' emergence as a Pacific Rim economic power and growth as a multi-ethnic cultural center. The city's population is swelling past 3 million, making it the nation's