<HEAD>150,000 Refugees from Beirut in South Lebanon ^With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The horror of the fighting in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> has sent 150,000 city residents fleeing for shelter in war-ravaged south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Many moved in with relatives. But hundreds are living in the wilderness, sleeping in their cars, in orange groves, or on the rough concrete gravel in unfinished buildings. A nine-month-pregnant woman is staying with her three children and 45 other refugees at one of the incomplete structures. They sleep on the ground without mattresses or blankets. `` I need milk to feed my children, and to give to my baby who is due any minute now,'' said <PERSON> Alliyeh </PERSON> <PERSON> Khodor </PERSON>, 24. She fled her house in southern <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> on March 14, a week after the latest round of fighting erupted between Christian and allied Syrian and Druse forces around the capital. Police say at least 180 have been killed and more than 600 injured the fighting. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping force in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> are trying to ease refugees' plight with food handouts and blankets. `` So far we have been able to provide wheat, sugar, canned food and blankets,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> spokesman who refused to be identified by name. `` But our stocks are running thin.'' The influx has boosted the population of south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> by 30 percent, causing acute food and gas shortages, said a police spokesman who by custom is not identified by name. Spokesmen for the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> force said at least 45,000 migrants are staying in the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> area of operations. The rest of the refugees, which they estimate