<HEAD>Jerusalem's Old City: Fault Line of Arab-Israeli Conflict</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The walled <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, dotted with shrines sacred to Moslems, Jews and Christians, is the major fault line of the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict where tensions frequently burst to the surface. On Tuesday, Palestinians buried an Arab resident of the <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s Moslem quarter who was shot by an Israeli dressed in army fatigues. The angry Palestinians shouted: `` Teach the Jews a lesson! Everything Jewish in this town should be burned!'' `` We are living inside a powder keg,'' said <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Sublaban </PERSON>, 40, the owner of a souvenir shop in the city's Moslem quarter. `` The slightest provocation can make all the resentments erupt to the surface.'' Responsibility for the submachine gun attack Monday was claimed by a Jewish extremist group known as the Sicarites. The group, which takes its name from ancient Jewish assassins of biblical times, said it was avenging Palestinian stoning attacks on Jews. Tension in the <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> rose Friday when rocks hurled by Palestinian rioters during a clash in the <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aqsa </ORGANIZATION> mosque compound fell on Jews worshipping at the adjacent Wailing Wall, the holiest site in Judaism. `` Radicalism on both the Arab and Jewish sides have sharpened the situation,'' Police Minister <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bar </PERSON> <PERSON> Lev </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio. `` Arabs throw rocks at the <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> and a Jew kills Arabs. There is no solution, it only heats up the conflict.'' About 17,000 Moslems and 2,000 Jews live in separate enclaves inside ancient <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s crowded square mile of narrow cobblestone alleyways, houses and shops. Enemies yet neighbors, they carry separate passports and rarely