<HEAD>Government Calls Winter Wheat's Condition ``Mostly Fair''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Winter wheat across the nation is in `` mostly fair'' condition, although the crop has declined in the central <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>, a government report said Tuesday. `` In <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, winter wheat condition deteriorated and was mostly very poor to poor,'' the Joint Agricultural Weather Facility said. `` As fields broke dormancy, winterkill continued to become more evident. Insect and disease problems, however, were below normal.'' The facility, operated by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> departments, said the <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> crop was mostly good to fair, and in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> winter wheat was reported in mostly fair to poor condition. Conditions were reported as of the week of April 3-9. Dry soils since winter wheat was planted last fall have stunted development severely in many areas. Elsewhere in the plains region, winter wheat in <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> was said to be in mostly fair condition, although winterkill became evident as the dormant crop began to green up this spring. The crop was reported mostly good to fair in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, and mostly fair to good in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, winter wheat was mostly fair to good, with some replanting in the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> crop was mostly poor, with winterkill becoming more widespread in several counties. Winter wheat was said to be in mostly good to excellent condition in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, and mostly good in the Corn Belt. In the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> and Southeast,