<FIRST>r w AM-Amtrak-NTSB     04-11 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amtrak-NTSB,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Says Warped Track Caused Derailment, Blames Rail Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal investigators on Tuesday blamed `` inadequate track inspection and maintenance procedures'' by the <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> Northern Railroad for the derailment last summer of an <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> passenger train in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. The train, which was bound from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, derailed Aug. 5 near <LOCATION> Saco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mon. </LOCATION>, when it struck track that had been warped by temperatures near 100 degrees. The accident injured 165 people, about a dozen of them seriously. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> in its report on the accident said Tuesday it was caused by shifting of track just ahead of the <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> train. The board said the shifting was caused by the intense heat, but that track conditions and the danger of such buckling should have been apparent to <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> Northern. The probable cause of the accident, said the safety board in its final report, `` was <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION>'s inadequate track inspection and maintenance procedures which resulted in a thermally induced lateral shift of the track structure in front of -LRB- the -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> train.'' The board continued that `` the lateral shift occurred when the train was closer than the 2,478 feet necessary'' to bring the train to a safe stop. The train was traveling at an authorized speed of 79 miles an hour. `` There was nothing that the engine crew could have done ... to have avoided or decreased the severity of the accident after they observed the shifted track,'' said the report. The derailment caused five of the train's cars to topple after leaving the tracks. The 12-car train was carrying 375 passengers and about a dozen crewmembers. The safety board blamed some of the injuries on `` the lack of effective restraint devices'' that caused some items to fly around inside the cars. While the board did not fault <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> for the accident, the report called on the passenger railroad to improve its training and procedures for evacuating passengers in such circumstances. The safety board also called on <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> to improve its track inspection procedures and make available to inspectors devices that could determine when excessive heat might cause track to warp.
