<HEAD>Fire Controlled At Huge Plant; Last Flames Expected Out Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An explosion and fire at in <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s huge east <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> refinery cut the plant's gasoline and jet fuel production cut by 25 percent, the company said. Monday's blast sent towering clouds of sooty smoke boiling into the sky from the 4 -LCB- - square-mile <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> plant and injured eight workers and firefighters with burns, smoke inhalation and shock Firefighters decided to allow the blaze to burn itself out and residual pockets of fuel continued burning Tuesday. The burned unit, a cracking column which separates crude oil into its various components from light fuels to heavy lubricants, produced about 10 percent of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>'s oil requirements, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> could not say if the production shortfall would cause any retail increase at the pumps in the western states, but that <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> planned to compensate by dipping into inventories and increasing production at other refineries. `` It's hard to isolate what the movement in prices ... might be; one thing we know is our costs will go up,'' he said. The company said the stricken unit could be out of commission for at least two months, but management would not speculate on repair and replacement costs. The 87-year-old plant handles 270,000 barrels of oil a day. <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> said company investigators were still trying to determine the cause of the lunch-hour eruption. The plant employs about 1,800 people. The Bay Area Air Quality Management District reported that although the smoke did not register on monitoring stations near the plant <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> might be liable for a $ 1,000 fine `` for creating a public nuisance.'' The smoke was not toxic, said <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Costa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Finucane </PERSON>, rating the smoke about as dangerous as that produced in a fireplace.
