<HEAD>Syrians Shell Christian Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian gunners shelled Christian areas Tuesday in spite of a 6-day-old truce called by the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, and <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> sent an envoy to work out a distribution plan for two shiploads of French humanitarian aid. Police said the howitzer shells landed in a scattered pattern in Christian territory and no casualties were reported. They said the Christians held their fire. Moslem-Christian artillery duels began five weeks ago and developed into the worst sectarian fighting since 1985 in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 14-year-old civil war Police give the casualties, nearly all civilians, as 180 killed and 619 wounded. Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, who commands the 20,000 Christians of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s army, imposed a blockade March 6 on illegal militia-run ports that deprive the government of an estimated $ 100 million a year in revenue. <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>'s Druse militia started shooting two days later and Syrian gunners soon joined them. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> has 40,000 soldiers in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kouchner </PERSON>, French minister for humanitarian assistance, arrived ahead of the two ships carrying food, fuel and medical supplies, which have caused an argument between Moslems and Christians. Moslems claim <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, from which <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> became independent in 1943, favors the Christians. The French government has expressed concern over the fate of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s Christians. <PERSON> Kouchner </PERSON> spent 45 minutes with acting Premier <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, who heads a Moslem cabinet that has competed with a Christian government led by <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> since a political crisis began in September. <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> convened his cabinet afterward, then issued a statement saying the Moslem government rejected `` the French donation until the French stand toward the <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> crisis is clarified.'' <PERSON> Kouchner </PERSON> told reporters <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> was determined to deliver the aid to `` all the Lebanese'' and would meet with several leaders to plan the distribution. He said <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> policy `` supports a political settlement in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON> has warned the French not to bring the ships into a Christian port. Before meeting in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, a Sunni Moslem, <PERSON> Kouchner </PERSON> conferred with <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Baabda </LOCATION>, the Christian suburb where the presidential palace is located. By unwritten agreement since 1943, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s president is a Christian, the premier a Sunni and the parliament speaker a Shiite Moslem. The relief ships left for <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> last week. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> has not said when they will arrive, but they are expected Wednesday. One carries food and fuel. The other is a hospital ship with beds, surgical facilities and medical supplies. Fear has been expressed that more fighting will accompany the ships' arrival. A <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> envoy who was in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> last week _ <PERSON> Jean-Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Deniau </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>'s foreign affairs committee _ was quoted Tuesday as saying it `` would be an act of war against <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'' to fire on the ships. `` If they fire, it is clear that they want to destroy <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>,'' he was quoted as saying in the Tours, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nouvelle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republique </ORGANIZATION> du Centre-Ouest. <PERSON> Youssef </PERSON> <PERSON> Aridi </PERSON>, a grocer in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, said: `` I think Wednesday will be a bad day. I wo n't leave home. If they shell the French, God knows what will happen.'' <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s latest government crisis began when President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>'s six-year term ended in September and <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> could not agree on a successor. <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON> chose <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, the army comnmander, to lead an interim administration and Moslems swore allegiance to <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, the incumbent premier. The army also split on sectarian lines, with <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> commanding the Christians and Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Sami </PERSON> <PERSON> Khatib </PERSON> taking charge of the 22,000 Moslems.
