 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and reporters since the existence of the partnership was disclosed last month. Mrs. <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> has acknowledged receiving less than $ 10,000 from the partnership for her work in setting up the deal and coordinating the promotional effort. <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said Tuesday his wife `` resents the implication'' in <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s complaint that she was used as a conduit to funnel money to him in violation of House rules. He said she has contacted an attorney to determine if she has grounds for legal action. In addition to the promotional deal, <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said the book involved a standard royalty contract in which he and his wife each received 3 percent royalties and <ORGANIZATION> Drake </ORGANIZATION> 2 percent. But <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> said the payments <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> received can not be characterized as royalties because of the unique promotional deal associated with the book. Consequently, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> argued, those payments are not exempt from the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rule limiting outside earned income, as royalties are. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> also alleged that the promotional deal involved four apparent violations of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> limitations on gifts, one possible conversion of campaign funds to personal use, two possible instances of conversion of government resources to personal use, one apparent violation of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> financial disclosure rules and one apparent violation of the campaign finance law.
