<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two major nursing-home groups filed suit against the government Tuesday to block provisions of a law requiring nursing homes to turn away the mentally ill and mentally retarded. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Car </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION> for the Aging said the federal government is requiring states to implement the law, which took effect Jan. 1, even though the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> has issued no regulations to guide them. They said the result is that the law will hurt the people it was intended to help by denying them admission to nursing homes even when no alternate care facilities are available. Nursing home applicants and patients who are mentally retarded or mentally ill `` are being held hostage by this legislation and its misguided implementation,'' said <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homes </ORGANIZATION> for the Aging, which represents about 2,500 nursing homes. Though he did not cite specific instances in which mentally ill or mentally retarded patients have been discharged from nursing homes, he said his concern was `` that could happen in the future.'' The suit was filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> for the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, naming <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>. Department officials had no immediate comment on the lawsuit. Under the law, nursing homes will lose federal Medicaid funds if they accept patients who suffer from mental illness or mental retardation unless they also need nursing home care. Nursing homes get about 44 percent of their revenues from the federal-state Medicaid program. Patients who have lived in a nursing home for fewer than 30 months also must be screened for mental illness and mental retardtion, under the law. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Willging </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents about 9,000 nursing homes, said that without regulations from the <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION>, nursing homes do n't know how to define mental illness. The law exempts Alzheimer's disease, but diagnosis of the condition is difficult and its victims are often classified as mentally ill, he noted. Depending on how mental illness is defined, an estimated 26,000 to 208,000 current residents of the 1.5 million Americans in nursing homes might have to be involuntarily discharged under the law, he said. With few alternate care facilities available in most areas, he said, many of these patients may be left homeless, without even basic levels of care. <PERSON> Willging </PERSON> and <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said the law is well-intentioned in that it seeks to ensure that the mentally ill and mentally retarded get the specialized treatment they need for their conditions. `` But it is equally important to provide some elementary protections,'' <PERSON> Willging </PERSON> said. `` We demand the horse be put before the cart.'' The suit asks the court to put the screening requirements of the law on hold until HHS issues implementing regulations. It also asks the court to prohibit application of the rules to private-pay patients. Restraining orders have been issued by courts in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> in response to suits filed by nursing-home groups, <PERSON> Willging </PERSON> said. A suit also has been filed in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, he said. Earlier this year, <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, then-deputy director of <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said the law was an effort to get states to develop group-home and community-based services for the mentally ill and mentally retarded Historically, it has been the states' responsibility to fund services and facilities for the mentally ill, he said. To avoid this cost, however, some states have sent these patients to nursing homes, where Medicaid picks up the tab for those who can not pay. More states have special facilities for the mentally retarded because Medicaid helps pay for them, but nursing home care for these patients is often cheaper, he said.
