 The Soviet <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> will cut the length of military service required for students who have completed higher education courses, the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said Tuesday. Under new regulations for conscription, students who graduate this spring will be required to serve only one year in the military instead of 18 months in the army and air force or two years in the navy, the news agency said. The new regulations were expected to begin with the spring intake of conscripts, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> announced in March that students could defer military service until after graduation, but it did not specify the length of service that would be required. Previously, all Soviet men between the ages of 18 and 25 were liable for the draft, and there were no exemptions for students. Changes in the conscription system have been under discussion for the past five years, and the program of officer training is also under review, according to the Communist youth newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION>. The new rules apply only to conscripts and not officers or officer candidates, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. About 75 percent of Soviet military personnel are conscripts. Changes in the draft law follow the announcement Dec. 7 by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> that Soviet troop strength would be cut by 500,000 and military spending would be reduced by 14 percent.
