<HEAD>County To Test Officers For Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Nassau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has begun random drug testing in certain narcotics squads, making it one of the first departments in the nation to test officers for drug use. Officers who fail the test will be fired, and officers who refuse to take it also may be dismissed. The program was announced to the 200 officers in the drug-fighting squads this week and is effective immediately. The policy follows a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision which last month upheld the right of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to randomly test employees who work on drug interdiction even without reasonable suspicion an officer has used drugs. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON>, attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benevolent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, said the union has not decided whether to challenge Nassau's new policy. The program is designed to make the public and officers confident of an officer's integrity, Commissioner <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rozzi </PERSON> said. He noted that the officers assigned to the drug units, including undercover agents and police lab workers, have ready access to drugs. `` Almost all of our officers are above reproach _ the finest in the country,'' said <PERSON> Rozzi </PERSON>, whose department on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> numbers 3,200. `` We want to be able to weed out the one or two who are not.'' For 15 years, the <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> department has drug-screened applicants, officers during their first year of probation, and