<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> lawmakers have ratified a bill requiring background checks and a seven-day waiting period for buyers of military-style semiautomatic assault weapons. The bill, prompted by January's schoolyard shooting in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and by an upswing in street violence involving semiautomatic weapons, was approved late Monday in the closing hours of the 1989 General Assembly session. The measure still must be signed by Gov. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaefer </PERSON>, whose support is expected. Under the legislation, state police would check the background of a prospective gun buyer before a sale could be completed. The sale would be canceled if police found evidence that the applicant was a drug addict, alcoholic, convicted felon or was mentally deranged. Purchases of 24 specific gun models are affected, and those who violate the law would be subject to prison terms of up to three years and maximum fines of $ 10,000. Earlier in the 90-day session, some legislators proposed banning the sale of semiautomatics altogether, but later modified the measure in the face of overwhelming resistance. In 1988, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> passed a bill eliminating cheap handguns known as Saturday Night Specials. The measure established a nine-member board to decide which guns may be manufactured and sold in the state. Gun control opponents spent $ 6 million in a losing effort to defeat that bill. Continued pressure from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rifle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has kept lawmakers leery of further weapons legislation. However, lawmakers around the nation have felt pressure to control the spread of semiautomatic weapons, particularly after January's schoolyard tragedy in <LOCATION> Stockton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, where a gunman killed five children and wounded 30 other people in a rapid burst of gunfire from an AK-47.
