<HEAD>Study: Long Waiting List for Military Child Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 25,000 children in military families nationwide are on waiting lists for child care despite <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> efforts to expand its child care program, according to a study released Tuesday. The survey, conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, found that military child care facilities are providing day care for about 62,000 children, an 82 percent increase over the end of the 1984 fiscal year. Two types of care are available to families living on <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> bases _ child development centers, provided in government-built and subsidized facilities by trained care givers; and family day care homes, usually provided in government housing by non-military spouses. The survey of 200 military installations in the continental <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> found that child development centers have the capacity to care for more than 38,500 children, while 4,557 day care homes can care for as many as 23,417 children. Eighty percent of the remaining 24,729 children, who are on waiting lists, need full-day care. The survey, by the congressional watchdog agency, had no information on nationwide spending for military child care. Worldwide, however, operating costs for child care centers totaled $ 101.6 million in fiscal 1985, including $ 31.4 million in federally appropriated funds, the report said. By fiscal 1987, federal spending had increased 39 percent, to $ 43.6 million out of a total cost of $ 134.3 million, the survey said. If the program is to continue to grow, many child care centers need to be renovated or built, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. Military parents' child care needs are complicated by the fact that they often work unusual hours, ca n't rely on extended family for help and, because of frequent moves, do n't have the support of an established neighborhood, according to the report.
