<HEAD>Military Provides Guarantees for Journalists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The military, criticized for killing two reporters last month, said Tuesday it will not fire on journalists' vehicles even if they ignore or inadvertently run a roadblock. Two reporters were killed and another seriously wounded in March by soldiers manning roadblocks. The incidents are being investigated, but the armed forces have acknowledged that in at least one of the cases the soldier fired without provocation. In another development, President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> returned to his duties at the Presidential Palace after five days of convalescence from side effects of cancer treatment. A document containing instructions on military relations with the press was signed Tuesday by Defense Minister Gen. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Vides </PERSON> <PERSON> Casanova </PERSON>. It says that if a news vehicle passes through a roadblock, soldiers manning the position `` will limit themselves to taking down the license plate number, to be reported to the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION>, which will take appropriate action. Under no circumstances will the vehicles or their occupants be fired upon.'' Security force roadblocks are common in zones where fighting is heaviest in this Central American country, ravaged by nine years of civil war between leftist guerrillas and the U.S.-backed government. News vehicles are identified by the local convention of affixing, with tape, the large letters `` TV'' on the windshield, sides, roof and back. They also fly small white flags out windows or from antennae. The document, to be distributed in the form of an order to military units nationwide, also prohibits the arrest of accredited journalists discovered in battle zones without a safe-conduct document from the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGAN