<HEAD>Rebel Soldiers Returning to Duty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> PORT-AU-PRINCE </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ Soldiers whose revolt was crushed by loyal troops over the weekend have begun returning to duty after Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Prosper </PERSON> <PERSON> Avril </PERSON>'s military government promised not to punish them. Radio Soleil, the Roman Catholic church radio station, said more than 230 of the <ORGANIZATION> Dessalines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barracks </ORGANIZATION>' 750 soldiers had reported to army headquarters by Tuesday morning. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Serge </PERSON> <PERSON> Elie </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> said Monday no rebels were being held prisoner. The government has said they will be treated `` with dignity'' and no reprisals will be taken. Two gunmen identified as Dessalines deserters hijacked a twin-engine airplane Monday that was carrying missionaries based in <LOCATION> Redlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, from <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. The hijackers diverted the plane to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and surrendered. The seven other passsengers and the pilot were not harmed. <PERSON> Avril </PERSON>'s 1,100-man Presidential Guard based at the National Palace stormed the adjoining <LOCATION> Dessalines </LOCATION> barracks Saturday to put down a rebellion among soldiers demanding that the general give up the presidency. Fighting began Friday night and lasted 20 hours. <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> told reporters Monday most of the cartridges used initially were blanks, in order to reduce casualties. He said the Saturday assault with live ammunition occurred after mortar shells from the <ORGANIZATION> Dessalines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barracks </ORGANIZATION> landed near the palace, killing three soldiers. Five soldiers were killed in the two days of fighting, and a sixth died Sunday while trying to recover an unexploded grenade, <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> said. He also reported one civilian killed and 43 soldiers and 32 civilians wounded. It remained unclear whether <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> would disband the <PERSON> Dessalines </PERSON>, widely regarded as the most repressive unit in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s 7,000-man army. Col. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Francois </PERSON>, its former commander, was said to have been given temporary asylum in the <ORGANIZATION> Vatica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. The government has identified <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> as one of four leaders of a coup attempt April 2. Negotiations continued between the government and the 414-member <ORGANIZATION> Leopards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Battalion </ORGANIZATION>, the other unit that rebelled last week. Lt. Col. <PERSON> Himmler </PERSON> <PERSON> Rebu </PERSON>, the commander, was deported after being named as a conspirator in the coup attempt. <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> said 12 Leopards had not returned to their base, but the battalion had accepted government authority. `` Everything is on the way to the re-establishment of order,'' Adjutant Gen. <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Jean-Pierre </PERSON> said Tuesday.
