<FIRST>r w AM-FusionConfusion     04-11 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fusion Confusion,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Fusion Experiments Still Leave Many Questions On Process</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite two tests that seem to confirm part of a <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> cold nuclear fusion experiment, experts said Tuesday that more questions need to be answered before most scientists accept there has been a breakthrough. `` We're all mystified by this and watching it,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Meade </PERSON>, head of fusion reaction research at <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION> niversity. `` It's the scientific way to be skeptical. That process is still going on.'' <PERSON> Meade </PERSON> and others said the experiments announced Monday at <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M and <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> did shed some light on what <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> officials claim is a demonstration of fusion at room temperature. But most experts remain unconvinced that fusion has actually taken place and some suggest the phenomenon may be something new to science. `` They -LRB- <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> researchers -RRB- have taken the position that it was a fusion reaction,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Soures </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rochester </ORGANIZATION> fusion scientist. `` But that has yet to proven.'' `` I think this whole thing may go down as one of the most bizarre episodes in 20th century science,'' he added. In an announcement two weeks ago, <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southhampton </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> said they had achieved fusion using ordinary laboratory equipment at room temperature. Their experiment used a rod of palladium and a coil of platinum immersed in a beaker of deuterium, an isotope of hydrogen commonly found in seawater. <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> said that when electrical power was applied to the coil for about 100 hours, it forced deuterium atoms into the palladium until they finally fused, producing energy in the form of heat. <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> claimed the device made four watts of energy for every watt of energy used. Fusion has been the goal of thousands of scientists around the world for more than a quarter century. It is the energy secret of the stars, the sun, and the reaction that gives the boom to the hydrogen bomb. If the reaction could be controlled, scientists believe it could be the ultimate energy source, giving virtually limitless electrical power using a cheap fuel extracted from sea water and producing only modest amounts of radiation hazard. In fusion, hydrogen atoms are forced together. As they fuse, they give off energy, neutrons and helium-3, a stable chemical. Fusion is the opposite of fission, the nuclear reaction that splits the atomic nucleus. Fission is the force that powers atomic power plants and nuclear bombs. At <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M, scientists said Monday an apparatus similar to the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> experiment did produce some excess energy, but the reaction was so small that their equipment was not sensitive enough to detect the flow of neutrons, a characteristic of fusion. A & amp; M's <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said his group could have come from some `` unusual chemical process'' and not from nuclear fusion. This possibility, he said, is being investigated. A similar experiment at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> did produce neutrons, causing researcher <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Livesay </PERSON> to announce, `` There's no question it's fusion. I still do n't believe it, even though I see it.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> experiment began producing neutron particles and probes measured a flow of about 560 neutrons an hour above the background radiation. However, <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahaffey </PERSON> said the team did not confirm that the experiment produced more energy than it used. <PERSON> Meade </PERSON> said fusion can not be confirmed until more laboratories have conducted the experiment and made precise measurements of both the heat production and the flow of neutrons. He said the rise in neutrons and in heat should `` track'' each other, that is, show by measurement to be directly related. `` It is not enough to just see some heat there and the hint of a few neutrons,'' said <PERSON> Meade </PERSON>. `` We need to be able to relate this energy to some process that would produce it.'' He said the amount of energy reported in the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> experiment would develop trillions of neutrons a second, and if the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> experiments matched the energy output, they, too, would have high neutron flow. `` They are missing billions of neutrons per second,'' said <PERSON> Meade </PERSON>. `` They hypothize that is may a different type of nuclear reaction than we have known. Physics experts around the world are trying to come up with some nuclear reaction that we have n't seen before. It possible, but not very probable.'' Both <PERSON> Meade </PERSON> and <PERSON> Soures </PERSON> said the energy surge seen in the experiment may be created by a `` battery effect.'' `` It takes weeks for the energy output to get up to the reported levels,'' said <PERSON> Soures </PERSON>. `` This suggests that it's operating more like a battery than fusion.'' He said the device could be storing the electrical energy put into the experiment and then discharging the power as heat when it becomes satuated. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Dolan </PERSON> of the Department of Energy laboratory in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, said that a good explanation of the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> experiment will not be developed until more experiments are conducted and the fundamental process is finally understood. `` Sometimes, these things could drag on for months before they are resolved,'' he said. `` But right now, I do n't think it is a breakthrough that will be useful.''
</TEXT>
