<HEAD>Drug Czar Charged, Denies Connection with Narcotics Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drug czar <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON>, believed to be the biggest cocaine dealer in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, was charged Tuesday with possession, trafficking and transportation of illegal drugs. `` I do n't know why they connect me with the cocaine business,'' he said in the 10th District Court after the charges were read. `` I have never had that type of dealings.'' The court is located inside the Southern Prison on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON> stood behind bars during the proceeding. He was asked if he used drugs and he replied, `` Yes, sporadically, but I'm not an addict.'' <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON> was moved under heavy guard before dawn from the Attorney General's office where he had been held since his arrest Saturday in <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION>. Nine others arrested in the investigation, including several of <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON>'s aides and the chief federal anti-drug official and five other ranking police officers in <LOCATION> Sinaloa </LOCATION> state, were jailed in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s Northern Prison. Authorities on Monday seized some of <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON>'s assets, including a hotel, pharmacy, real-estate company, bank accounts and other properties. No value was placed on the assets, but his net worth is estimated to exceed $ 500 million. He was asked in court how much he earned. He said he could not say. Judge <PERSON> Amado </PERSON> <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvardo </PERSON> said the charges against <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON> carry a sentence of seven to 15 years. The judge has three days to decide whether to issue an indictment and then a year to review the evidence and present the verdict. Attorney General <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> on Monday called <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON> `` the No. 1 drug trafficker in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>.'' In the northwestern state of <LOCATION> Sinaloa </LOCATION>, judicial police patrolled the residential zones in <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON>'s hometown of <LOCATION> Culiacan </LOCATION>, especially the districts where he owned property. <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON>, 43, was taken to the 10th District Court on the basis of a warrant the court issued for him in 1986 after the arrest of <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Devere </PERSON> <PERSON> Becerra </PERSON>. Parts of the 500-page court document read to <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON> were based on testimony by <PERSON> Devere </PERSON> <PERSON> Becerra </PERSON>, who allegedly was <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON>'s partner for a year or two beginning in 1983. <PERSON> Devere </PERSON> <PERSON> Becerra </PERSON> also has been linked to other drug traffickers, including <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>, who was arrested in the 1985 slaying of American <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON>. <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON> was sentenced in September 1988 to 34 years in prison after being convicted on drug-related charges. He has not been tried in the abduction, torture and killing of <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON>. That case is in a court in the western city of <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION>. During Tuesday's hearing, <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON> denied knowing <PERSON> Devere </PERSON> <PERSON> Becerra </PERSON> or at least four other reputed narcotics kingpins. He was not asked about <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>. <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> said Monday his office had no evidence linking <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON> directly to the killing of <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON>, but he said he was the `` intellectual author'' of the organization that murdered the agent. <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON> was asked by the court what he did between March and December of 1984 _ the period covered by <PERSON> Devere </PERSON> <PERSON> Becerra </PERSON>'s depositions He said, `` During this period I was only dedicated to my hotel business, and a concession for sales of building, along with various businesses in which I'm up to date on tax payments.'' He gave his profession as a businessman, said he was married and had four children and had attended junior high school. He also said he was a native of <LOCATION> Culiacan </LOCATION> and lived in <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallardo </PERSON> denied testimony in the court record that he used several airplanes, including his own $ 1.5 million Aerocommander, to transport drugs from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to various parts of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and sometimes across the border to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
