<HEAD>Police Quiz Nurses Aid Who Gave Early Tip on 49 ``Mercy Deaths''
^Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with police comments, detail. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VIE2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A nurse's aide who reported a suspicious death at a hospital last year was questioned Tuesday by police investigating four other nurse's aides who confessed to what they described as 49 `` mercy killings.'' All the patients at <LOCATION> Lainz </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> were elderly _ 75 years or older _ and were killed over the past six years with overdoses of medicine or by water forced into their lungs. Police said they doubted the claim of mercy killing because of the methods used. One investigator said the nurse's aides also admitted to killing patients they considered a nuisance. After a Cabinet meeting Tuesday, Chancellor <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Vranitzky </PERSON> spoke of the case as `` the most brutal and gruesome crime in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s history.'' The killings prompted <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Zilk </PERSON> to evoke <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> medical experiments at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> and other death camps. `` The death angels of Lainz remind me of the death angels of <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Zilk </PERSON> said during a televised debate late Monday. Nurse's aides <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Gruber </PERSON>, 25; <PERSON> Irene </PERSON> <PERSON> Leidolf </PERSON>, 27; <PERSON> Waltraud </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, 30, and <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON>, 50, are in custody, but no charges have been filed. Three were arrested Friday and one Sunday. Police said Ms. <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> admitted killing 39 patients, 22 of them by forcing water into their lungs, and Ms. <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON> to killing five patients, one with water. A fifth nurse's aide, Chilean-born <PERSON> Dorah </PERSON> <PERSON> Eugenie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrada-Avendano </PERSON>, was on vacation when a warrant for her arrest was issued, and she went to police Tuesday for questioning. Authorities said they doubted she was involved and speculated the other four implicated her because she reported her suspicions last year. The first deaths in the ward _ which has come to be known as `` The Death Pavilion'' _ occurred in 1983, but most were committed in the last two years, police said. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelbacher </PERSON>, a senior police investigator, said Tuesday that questioning of nursing personnel substantiated the assumption of `` knowledge and suspicion'' about the crimes committed at the hospital's <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. He said police got the impression staff members did not take rumors about the deaths seriously. <PERSON> Edelbacher </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the total of patients killed will probably rise above 49 with further investigation. As aides, the women were supposed to wash and feed patients, but not to give injections, according to hospital officials. Austrian radio said Ms. <PERSON> Ferrada-Avendano </PERSON> told police she knew of one murder and told a doctor about it. But <PERSON> Edelbacher </PERSON> said she knew of killings at the hospital two or three years before she first mentioned her suspicion last year. He said that as a single woman coming from abroad and having to look after a son, she was under constraint that made it hard for her to approach authorities. Police Chief <PERSON> Guenter </PERSON> <PERSON> Boegl </PERSON> has said the overdoses administered were insulin or tranquilizers. Police sources said aides plugged the noses of at least 23 victims and pumped water into their lungs. Investigators said each nurse knew the others were killing patients, and in some cases two nurses would act together. An unidentified man, confirming a newspaper interview, told Austrian TV he saw <PERSON> Waltraud </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> administer sleeping medication to a 86-year-old male patient who died hours later. The man refused to face the camera or give his name. <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON>, who heads the department where the murders occurred, said he and his doctors could not have known about the mass slayings because the crimes were committed in a secret and sophisticated way. <PERSON> Edelbacher </PERSON> said police met `` a wall of silence'' when they tried to get the name of the doctor said to have been told about suspicious events in the ward. <PERSON> Zilk </PERSON> read a police statement that said the doctor, when finally identified, refused to name his informant. The mayor appointed a commission to consider possible negligence at the hospital, <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'s fourth largest.
