<HEAD>California Water Program Renewed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, faced with a long-running fight over central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> water, announced the renewal Tuesday of a long-term contract to supply water to farmers despite objections from environmentalists. But Interior Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> directed that an environmental assessment of the lease renewal be done and he suggested that state officials and other interested groups could solve any environmental problems. While the lease only involves the Orange Cove Irrigation District in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joaquin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, the action is likely to set a precedent for other central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> irrigation projects which serve farmers who also rely on the delivery of federal water through an elaborate system of dams and canals. Environmentalists have opposed a renewal of the long-term leases because they argue the leases lock the government into supplying a certain volume of water well into the next century at a time when rapid population growth also is putting new demands on non-farming water needs. As water continues to be diverted for both agriculture and urban use, streams will dry up and seasonal wetlands, which support migratory waterfowl, will disappear, the critics maintain. Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on water, power and offshore energy resources, sharply criticized the decision to resume renewing the leases at a time when there are uncertainties about their environmental impact `` This decision further corrodes the environmental credentials of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Block </PERSON>, an attorney who represents several environmental groups that have challenged the lease renewals, said, `` It's kind of backward to sign the leases and then order an environmental assessment.'' The Friant Unit of the Central Valley Project, as the huge irrigation system is called, receives 1.5 million acre-feet of water a year from <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reclamation </ORGANIZATION>, providing water for both large and small farms and orchards. The decision to renew the lease came as different agencies of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration also continued to disagree sharply on whether new <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> water contracts running 40 years should be issued without resolving all their potential environmental ramifications. After the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> indicated last November that it planned to renew the 40-year leases without first developing formal environmental impact statements, the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> challenged the leases, elevating the matter to the White House. More than a dozen environmental groups also protested and the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> filed suit in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> arguing that another 40-year water commitment is such a significant act that it requires a formal environmental assessment under the National Environmental Policy Act. A federal judge recently said, in response to the suit, the leases could be issued, but he reserved the right to void any such lease, depending on the outcome of the government debate over environmental issues. The president's <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> has scheduled meetings in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> on Thursday and Monday to gather information on the environmental issues surrounding the lease renewal controversy. While the presidential council has no authority to block the leases or order environmental assessments, its opinions on such matters historically have carried considerable weight among federal agencies and in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. In a statement, <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> said the department action on the Orange Cove lease renewal should not have an impact on the <ORGANIZATION> CEQ </ORGANIZATION> proceedings. He said he has ordered the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reclamation </ORGANIZATION> to proceed with an environmental assessment of continuing water deliveries to the massive Central Valley Project, of which <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cove </ORGANIZATION> is only a small part. `` The renewal of long-term water supply contracts may pose legitimate environmental concerns,'' said <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>, adding that the assessment he ordered should be `` considered by the state and -LRB- local -RRB- districts as they adopt environmentally sensitive operating procedures and water policies.'' `` That is essentially different than doing an EIS -LRB- environmental impact statement under federal law -RRB-,'' suggested <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanderson </PERSON>, director of the office of federal activities at the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. He said <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> officials are essentially `` sidestepping'' the National Environmental Policy Act in the procedures being used to consider the environmental issues. `` Our position -LRB- at <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is the entire water issue for <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> needs to be reviewed in light of today's environmental standards and particularly the environmental requirements 40 years hence,'' said <PERSON> Sanderson </PERSON> in an interview. <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> said the lease renewal would encourage increased water conservation among the farmers by charging `` substantially higher prices'' for the water. Uder the new contract with <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cove </LOCATION>, the cost of federal water would quadruple from $ 3.50 to $ 14.94 per acre foot, he said. An acre foot is an amount of water need to flood an acre of land one foot deep, or about 350,000 gallons.
