PERSON> on a time agreement for debating the plan and said he hoped the floor debate could come Thursday `` This legislation is the result of a great many hours of work by members on both sides of the aisle,'' said <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said he wished there was sentiment in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to approve military aid to the Contras but conceded: `` The votes are n't there.'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> then applauded <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> for striking the deal for humanitarian aid for the Contras, saying the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> needed to `` remain a player'' in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in case <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Sandinista government reneges on commitments to democratic reforms. `` I'm not under any illusions that <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> is suddenly going to be a good boy in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said, referring to the Nicaraguan president.
