<HEAD>April Chill Threatens Crops in the South</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Temperatures dipped below freezing Tuesday through much of the nation east of <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION> and in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, where farmers scurried to save their crops. More than 40 cities reported record lows. The low of 29 degrees at <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> was a record April, and lows of 31 degrees at <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, and 26 at <LOCATION> Hot </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, tied records for the month. Frost and freeze warnings were posted Tuesday night for parts of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> fruit growers assessed the damage from the cold snap that apparently cut heavily into peach, plum and strawberry crops. The cold wave sent temperatures into the upper 20s in many parts of the state and left behind dead or dying plums and peaches, officials said. Apple and pear crops weathered better because they had not yet bloomed as much as the peaches, plums and strawberries. In <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, a record low of 28 degrees had apple, peach and plum farmers worried about their crops. In <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, many growers rushed Monday night to light smudge pots and activate irrigation systems to save their crops as overnight lows dipped to the 20s in much of the state. In <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, a record-breaking springtime snow hit the eastern part of the state early Tuesday, dusting streets and lawns but causing few