<HEAD>Bush Administration To Appeal Wheelchair Lifts Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government wants to appeal a decision requiring wheelchair lifts on all new public buses, saying the ruling would cost the nation's mass transit systems $ 90 million a year. Groups representing the disabled praised the Feb. 13 ruling by the 3rd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> as a means to help put handicapped people into the mainstream, but transit agencies said the costly lifts are rarely used. In petitioning Monday for a rehearing by the full court, the government said the ruling contradicted <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' intent. In addition, the government argued, the court failed to comprehend the full cost of the order. In the 2-1 decision, the court ordered the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> to rewrite regulations that allow communities to offer only `` paratransit'' service, such as van rides, to the disabled. The court said the 24-hour reservations that van riders need hindered spontaneous use of mass transit. The judges said instead that all new buses must be equipped with lifts. Since the decision, disabled people nationwide have demonstrated in hopes of persuading the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to allow the ruling to stand. The case was brought by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disabled </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accessible </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> and other groups for handicapped people. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Gold </PERSON>, an attorney for ADAPT, said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's decision to appeal is `` a slap in the face'' and renders the president's pledge of a `` kinder, gentler nation'' a hollow promise. ` It'll keep disabled people out of the mainstream and out of jobs for years and years to come,'' he said. In its petition, the government argued the legislation does not require `` wholesale restructuring of mass-transit services or imposition of the attendant financial burdens on an already overburdened public transportation system.'' The government said transit agencies across the country would pay $ 90 million a year for the lifts. In addition to $ 10,000 for each lift, the government said, maintenance and operating expenses would add $ 9,600 over 12 years.
