<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted 7-6 Tuesday night to approve a two-year contract keeping embattled <PERSON> Laval </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> in charge of the nation's oldest school system. The decision on the divisive issue was made on the deadline set by the board. It was announced by committee President <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> after members met behind closed doors for about two hours. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said he was delighted with the vote and looked forward `` to continuing to work for the young people of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>.'' He admitted having had some differences with committee members but said he believed he could work with them productively. `` It's not a working situation,'' retorted committee member <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cappucci </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> opponent. `` I do n't see how Dr. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> thinks he'll be able to get anything done. `` If I were him, I'd see the handwriting on the wall, realize what I've tried to do has n't worked and bow out,'' <PERSON> Cappuci </PERSON> said. `` He is not the man for the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> job.'' But committee member <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Nucci </PERSON>, who supports <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, said it was everyone's duty to try to make the uneasy union work. `` I hope they realize that personal vendettas have to be put aside in the interest of the school system,'' <PERSON> Nucci </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> had spent the past two weeks trying to work out a new contract with three of the school committee members. Under Tuesday night's action, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> is subject to a professional review every six months, at which time the committee can reconsider his contract. The arrival of <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, whose four-year contract expires in June, was heralded as a mature step for <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. A black man was going to run schools in a city that erupting in racial violence over federal court-ordered busing in 1974. Only days after <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> was hired, he asked for and got a $ 15,000 raise, to make his yearly salary $ 85,000. Since then, white flight to private schools has left the system mostly black. Of the system's 1972 enrollment of 96,000, 60 percent was white. Today, there are 59,000 students, 24 percent of them white. Critics of the 53-year-old <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> native complain he is aloof and autocratic. `` This is n't a racial issue, it's a competence and quality issue,'' school committee member <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis-Mullen </PERSON>, who is white and is one of <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s fiercest detractors, said Monday. `` He's a diligent worker, but his approach is n't meeting the needs of the children of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>.'' `` He lacks the insight and the philosophy that this system needs to move forward,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON> said. `` Although we've had $ 100 million added to the budget -LRB- now $ 361 million -RRB- since Dr. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> arrived, the dropout rate has increased.'' Supporters praise <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s hard work and honesty, saying he needs more time. `` You really ca n't get anything done changing horses in <LOCATION> midstream </LOCATION>. Just changing who it is right now is n't going to change a thing,'' said <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON>, a former school social worker and one of four black school committee members. In a self-assessment requested by the <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> gave himself high marks for dedication and for raising math and reading scores on national standardized tests and for lowering the dropout rate. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> says fewer youngsters are quitting