<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the most abrupt changes ever taken by those who seek to direct the American economy's course occurred about 15 years ago under circumstances somewhat similar to those of today. It was during the administration of <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, and inflation was on everyone's mind. The popular patriotic slogan of the day was `` Whip Inflation Now.'' It was printed on lapel buttons and splashed in advertisements. The campaign had an ignominious ending when the facts were realized _ that the nation was stumbling into recession and that recession far more than inflation was the big threat to the economy. It was not the first time the economic ship of state had been nearly driven onto the shoals and it was n't the last either. Almost all of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s recent presidents have been accused of erratic or even irresponsible steering. In relatively recent history, for example, <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON>, <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> have suffered criticisms for their tenure at the wheel. But nothing quite matches the abrupt realization in 1974 that the economy was headed to recession while all eyes were on inflation. And now, some critics contend there could be a repeat of the scenario in 1989. These critics can not as yet demonstrate their thesis by means of the popular statistics, which show the economy still has some forward momentum. But when you're steering a ship as big as the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy you never really know. When you flip the control buttons or turn the wheel a few degrees, for example, nothing seems to happen. A big ship does n't turn on a dime; it takes time to observe a change And when change comes you can not reverse it quickly. In effect, gloomy analysts are saying that maybe too many buttons have been pushed already, and that while we have n't seen the effect so far it is bound to show up in the next few months. Therefore, they say, beware of recession. Adding conviction to their fears, or vice versa, is the uncanny coincidence of the same man being in the control room. In 1974, as chairman of the President's <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> led the inflation fight. Today, as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, he has given inflation priority over recession. Few economists doubt <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>'s knowledge, or that he is capable of absorbing wisdom from experience, but one of them, <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinemann </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ladenburg </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Thalmann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a securities firm, offers this typical cautionary view: `` In sum, we think the economy is vulnerable. A slowdown, if not worse, is in the cards. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>'s zeal to Whip Inflation Now is commendable. But let's hope he does n't give us a replay of the crunch of 1974.'' The question, says <PERSON> Heinemann </PERSON>, is whether <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> will get the mild slowdown he wants, `` or will we go through something more sinister?'' In short, will the economy scrape bottom and continue on its way? Or will it run aground, spring a leak and spill its energy like the Exxon Valdez?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, April 12</NOTE>
