<HEAD>Lebanese Villlagers Get Their Wish _ The Irish are Staying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with 7 grafs, Irish decide to stay in Lebanon, picking
up 7th graf pvs, ``On March 30 ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Villagers in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> got their wish. The Irish government has decided to keep its 750-man batallion in the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping forces here. The government in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> had been reconsidering the Irish battalion's presence in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> because four of its soldiers had been killed and one wounded in three attacks in the past three months. Three of them were killed by a landmine March 21. `` We greatly need the Irish contingent in <LOCATION> south </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> <PERSON> Fawaz </PERSON>, the mayor of <LOCATION> Tibnin </LOCATION>, a town 11 miles north of the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> border. The estimated 100,000 Shiite Moslems living in 20 hamlets around <LOCATION> Tibnin </LOCATION>, the Irish headquarters, `` enjoy their protection,'' <PERSON> Fawaz </PERSON> said. Before making the decision, the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> reviewed a report by Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Tadhg </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>, chief of staff of the Irish army, who had come here to investigate the landmine explosion March 21. The Cabinet renews <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s commitment every six months, and the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> political opposition had called for a policy review after the deaths. The fourth death occurred earlier. `` Our presence here is very vital to the security of the area and to the locals who depend on our humanitarian aide,'' said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> McMahon </PERSON>, commander of the Irish contingent in the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> UNIFIL </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-. On March 30, hundreds of <LOCATION> Tebnin </LOCATION>'s 5,000 residents participated in a memorial ceremony for the three Irish soldiers killed by the landmine. `` The Irish contingent lives among its people in the south,'' said one of the banners at the ceremony. `` Aggression against it is aggression on the southerners.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping force, made up of 5,800 personnel from nine nations, has monitored a narrow strip of 65 towns and villages in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> since March 1985. The population in the force's area of operation increased from about 50,000 when the force first arrived to about a half million people today. `` Before <ORGANIZATION> UNIFIL </ORGANIZATION> came to south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> ... the area was a free terrain to militiamen and terrorists who spread fear and death everywhere,'' said <PERSON> Fawaz </PERSON>, 64, who has been mayor for 20 years. `` Now everyone is moving around here peacefully and freely, thanks to the Irish battalion.'' An Irish sergeant about to be moved out on routine rotation said he was leaving with mixed feelings. `` There are a lot of poor people here who are in great need of our humanitarian work, which is worth risking my life for,'' said the sergeant who could not allow his name to be used because of standing regulations. An Irish major at headquarters in <LOCATION> Tebnin </LOCATION> said it `` would be a fire zone without us.'' `` When the Irish battalion first came here, the villagers did not have any electricity and had shortages of water,'' he said, `` But we helped them, and now they are confident in their future because of us.'' The Irish battalion has lost 30 soldiers in attacks by various groups over the years. Investigations were still under way to determine who planted the landmine that exploded under a <ORGANIZATION> UNIFIL </ORGANIZATION> jeep near <LOCATION> Haddatha </LOCATION> on March 21 and killed the three soldiers, Lt. Col. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said. The other two recent attacks were carried out by the Israeli-backed <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lebanon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- SLA -RRB- militia, which controls a narrow strip of Lebanese territory that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> refers to as its `` security zone.'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> maintained the zone when it pulled out the bulk of its invading army from south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in the summer of 1985, ending a three-year occupation. The terrain, which extends from the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> in the west to the slopes of snow-peaked <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hermon </LOCATION> in the east, serves as a buffer against cross-border infiltrations by Palestinian guerrillas into northern Israeli settlements. Col. <PERSON> McMahon </PERSON> blamed <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lebanon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> attacks on the Irish battalion. He said such hostilities were due to `` the lack of control from the Israeli army command on the <ORGANIZATION> SLA </ORGANIZATION> militiamen.'' <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Fawaz </PERSON>, the son of <LOCATION> Tebnin </LOCATION>'s mayor who owns a gift shop near the Irish battalion headquarters, said, `` <LOCATION> Tebnin </LOCATION> residents notify the Irish command about the possibility of any attack on them that we come to know of.'' The younger <PERSON> Fawaz </PERSON> stressed the economic value that the Irish battalion represents to the area. The troops spend at least $ 500,000 annually on souvenirs and goods they buy duty-free from local stores.
</TEXT>
