<FIRST>s a BC-MissouriAbortion-Choice Adv16   04-11 1193</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Missouri Abortion-Choice, Adv 16,1228</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice Forces: `I Say God Is on My Side, Too'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Suggested for use with AM-Missouri Abortion-Anti, b0566.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 On April 26, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> will convene for a 60-minute hearing on one of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s most polarizing issues _ abortion. The debate centers on a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> law that restricts abortion and declares that human life begins at conception. The two sides in this <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> case represent in microcosm the deeply divided sentiments felt across the country. In two stories, part of an intermittent series on abortion issues, The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> profiles key players in this <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> case: the pro-choice advocates and the clinic at the heart of the dispute, and the leader of the anti-abortion forces, a man committed to a fight he sees as good vs. evil.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By SHARON COHEN</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> B.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Isaacson-Jones </PERSON> has days when she knows that dressing in red will provoke the ugly taunts again. `` <PERSON> B.J. </PERSON>, you're wearing red,'' scream the protesters sometimes gathered outside her office. `` Does that match the blood on your hands?'' The taunts have taken a toll on the director of <ORGANIZATION> Reproductive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, the abortion clinic at the heart of an emotional and explosive debate before the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's not unusual for me to close my office door and sob,'' she said. `` I'm proud of the way I live my life. It's hard when you're standing close to people and you can feel the hatred I do n't hate people.'' The intense feelings are likely to grow even stronger as April 26 draws nearer, the day the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> hears arguments over a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> statute that could chip away or overturn the 1973 ruling that legalized abortion. For anti-abortion advocates who've been waiting and working for this day for 16 years, it's a time of great hope. But for pro-choice supporters, just as eager to prevent this moment, it's a time of high anxiety. `` We are gravely concerned about this case,'' said <PERSON> Isaacson-Jones </PERSON>, whose non-profit clinic is the largest in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. `` What's at stake here is women's lives. It's that complicated and that simple.'' Missouri's pro-choice forces have grown from a small underground movement to a group of determined activists challenging a state whose Legislature has passed anti-abortion measures by 5-1 majorities. Two veteran advocates are key players in this case: <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Susman </PERSON>, a lawyer who will be arguing his fifth <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> abortion case before the high court, and <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Widdicombe </PERSON>, a former nurse at a Roman Catholic hospital and the founder of the clinic. Together, with <PERSON> Isaacson-Jones </PERSON>, they've shared not only their convictions, but also death threats, pickets at home or outside the clinic, obscene phone calls and harassment of their families. <PERSON> Susman </PERSON>, who represents the clinic, says someone once placed a bogus newspaper ad saying his house was for sale. A picket sued him for $ 250,000, claiming he'd assaulted her as he escorted a woman into another clinic where protesters were gathered. A jury cleared him. Reproductive Health is only one of seven plaintiffs _ Planned Parenthood of <LOCATION> Greater </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> is another _ but it has been the target of some of the most vicious attacks. Once, protesters stood on clinic desks and jumped through a reception window. In 1986, five gallons of gas were poured under the waiting room door and ignited. The blaze caused more than $ 100,000 damage. No one was arrested. `` This is a very violent movement,'' said <PERSON> Widdicombe </PERSON>, now a consultant for <ORGANIZATION> Voters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> For </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Choice </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` I think it has become a rapidly escalating war in the last 10 years.'' Abortion opponents in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, however, insist they repudiate violence and say verbal harassment is the wrong way to sway hearts and minds. `` If I have a sincere desire to point out the error of their ways, I'm not going to be able to accomplish that by screaming and hollering at them,'' said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> anti-abortion leader. The name-calling and pickets do prompt soul-searching. `` I stand in the shower the next morning and go over everything that was said,'' said <PERSON> Isaacson-Jones </PERSON>, who started at the clinic as a volunteer. `` I think, could they possibly be right? I go back stronger in my conviction. I will examine that again. I know I shall. `` But what I return to are the faces of the women I see,'' she added. `` I always, always understand the reason why a woman has chosen to terminate her pregnancy. I may not like the reasons she's waited so long ... `` The antis say God's on their side,'' she said. `` I say God's on my side as well. Isaacson-Jones' support of abortion rights stems from her high school days in the'60s when she saw pregnant classmates shunned and forced to drop out of school. `` I realized the incredible impact of one sexual experience on the rest of a woman and her family's life,'' she said. Today, she runs a clinic with 64 staff members, 35 volunteers and two offices. It counsels 15,000 women each year; more than 8,500 choose abortion. The women come from eight states: <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; 30 percent are poor. It's a long way from the late'50s, when <PERSON> Widdicombe </PERSON>, then a nurse, saw women disfigured trying to abort themselves, sometimes with lye. She later worked at a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> hospital, caring for new mothers in the labor and delivery section, then spending her free time arranging legal and illegal abortions _ sometimes as far away as <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. `` The hospital found that totally incongruent,'' <PERSON> Widdicombe </PERSON> said. She resigned. It was a scary time, too. `` There was a level of paranoia, absolutely,'' <PERSON> Widdicombe </PERSON> said. `` I did think about what it would be like to go to jail.'' <PERSON> Susman </PERSON> provided legal advice at the time. He now represents about 20 abortion clinics nationwide on a part-time basis, estimating reproductive issues account for about 10 percent of his work. In 1973, <PERSON> Widdicombe </PERSON> opened the clinic. Three hundred protesters marched outside. `` I though we'd just provide a clinic and work ourselves out of business,'' she said. `` It was pretty naive. We really felt we would decrease the need for abortion'' with education and research. Pro-choice leaders say they've been far less successful in organizing than their opposition. They also claim abortion foes misrepresent their cause. `` We have allowed this small group to define pro-choice as pro-abortion,'' said <PERSON> Isaacson-Jones </PERSON>. `` Think about the vivid pictures the anti-abortion people -LRB- display -RRB-. Who's going to argue with that? They have signs ... ` Money, Blood, Murder' ... That's not the reality of choice. Unlike her opponents, <PERSON> Isaacson-Jones </PERSON> says she is n't interested in converting anyone. `` I really do n't want to change their minds,'' she said. `` I wish they'd leave us alone and allow us to work in dignity.'' <PERSON> Susman </PERSON> expresses optimism about this case: `` I do not believe the court is prepared to turn back the clock 16 years.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> is the AP <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> regional reporter, based in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 16</NOTE>
