<SECOND>PM-Diaper Suit, Bjt,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Procter &amp; Gamble, Kimberly-Clark Battle In Diaper Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A battle between industry giants over super-absorbent diapers _ and the millions of dollars that come through their sale _ has opened in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court here. In the case, <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> charges that the design of its highly successful super-absorbent Pampers was copied by <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in developing super-absorbent Huggies. The huge consumer products company wants <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Falcon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawkins </ORGANIZATION> to order <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> to stop manufacturing the Huggies and remove them from store shelves. The company also is seeking unspecified monetary damages. The stakes are high, for making disposable diapers is a $ 3.3 billion-a-year business, according to court records. <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, is the industry leader, with 47 percent of the market. Dallas-based <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> is No. 2 with about 30 percent, industry analysts say. As the trial got under way Monday, attorneys crowded the courtroom while scattered along the jury box were boxes and bags of diapers. The case is expected to last at least three weeks. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerstein </PERSON>, representing <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> P </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; G came up with the idea that made super absorbent diapers possible and took out a patent on the development. The breakthrough, he said, allowed the manufacture of diapers that are generally thinner but more absorbent than regular, more bulky disposables. `` We stayed within the system while <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> disregarded and took unfair advantage of the system,'' he told <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> in his opening argument. P & amp; G Researcher <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Weisman </PERSON> developed a means for combining wood pulp fluff and super absorbent materials in the diaper to allow it to be made thinner, <PERSON> Gerstein </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gerstein </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> copied the idea shortly after the Pampers were test marketed in <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, in 1984. The introduction of the new diapers `` turned the diaper world on its ear,'' he said. But attorney <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, representing <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` This case is about two fiercely competitive companies each trying to improve baby diapers.'' He charged that P & amp; G never had a valid patent because it withheld important test information from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Patent Office. In addition, he said, the system <PERSON> Weisman </PERSON> developed was already covered in a British patent for super-absorbing materials issued to an Italian inventor in 1979. `` In order to have a valid patent, you ca n't be the second person or the 10th person -LRB- to invent something -RRB-. You have to be the first,'' he said. White argued that <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> had widespread experience with super-absorbent materials as early as 1977 in the manufacture of tampons and adult diapers. `` <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> did n't need lessons from anyone about super absorbent products,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said, noting that `` the only things our scientists learned from the <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION> diapers was how not to make a diaper.'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said the problem with the Pampers when they were introduced was that the super-absorbing material would come off on the skin of babies. It was a problem <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> was trying to address in its own labs at the time, he said, adding the company eventually developed a system of putting the material farther away from the babies' skin _ a system for which the company has been awarded a patent. The case is being heard in a non-jury proceeding. It was brought in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> because <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> runs a diaper manufacturing plant in <LOCATION> Beech </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>.
