<HEAD>Dollar Inches Up, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s key index rebounded sharply today while the dollar inched up against the Japanese yen after remarks by Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> about his links to a stock scandal reassured Japanese investors, dealers said. The dollar closed at 132.62 yen, up 0.09 yen from the previous day's 132.53-yen finish. It opened at 132.87 yen and ranged between 132.60 yen and 132.89 yen. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which fell 186.03 points on Monday, shot up today by 250.56 points, or 0.76 percent, closing at 33,249.58. `` Early morning trading started amid a cautious mood concerning what Prime Minister <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> was going to say before <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Kenji </PERSON> <PERSON> Ishizuka </PERSON> with <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` But the index started to rise as participants discovered <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said nothing worse than what had already been disclosed,'' he added. Volume traded on the first section in the first hour was only 200 million shares, but activity quickened later, and the full day's estimated volume was 1.1 billion shares, <PERSON> Ishizuka </PERSON> said. Addressing Parliament Tuesday morning, <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said he had received 130 million yen -LRB- about $ 1 million -RRB- in donations from <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the firm at the heart of a major stock-profiteering and bribery scandal. But he denied taking bribes and continued to reject opposition calls for his resignation. Investors were more or less reassured as <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said nothing new, while agreeing to give a parliamentary committee records of donations and stock profits he and his office have received, <PERSON> Ishizuka </PERSON> said. Opposition parties have halted parliamentary proceedings, demanding a full accounting of ruling <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> politicians' involvement in the scandal. In currency dealings, there was some yen buying as exchange market participants also were reassured by <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s remarks, said a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. He said the exchange rate was likely to change little in the next few days as the market awaits the release of major indicators for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy later this week. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is to announce the nation's trade figures for February and wholesale price index for March.
