 <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> announced Tuesday it will sell 194,000 acres of timberlands in western <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Crown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> for about $ 230 million. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> first announced plans to sell its northwest timberlands in 1983, and the agreement with Crown represents all but about 16,000 acres of the land to be sold. `` As we indicated in 1983, our northwest timberlands are best suited for producing lumber and building materials products which are not strategic directions for <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> chairman <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lippincott </PERSON> said. Pulp and paper manufacturing at <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Everett </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION> mill, which typically receives only a small amount of its wood fiber from the northwest timberlands, will not be affected. The agreement calls for Crown Pacific, of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, to supply wood fiber to the mill from the purchased land. The sale, which is subject to approval by <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>'s board of directors, is expected to be completed this summer.
