<HEAD>Wheat Futures Gain On Report Of Declining Crop Status</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wheat futures prices moved moderately higher today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> on signs of a deteriorating winter wheat crop. Corn and soybean futures were narrowly mixed. In its weekly report on crop conditions, released Monday after the markets closed, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> found a net decline in the condition of the winter wheat crop during the week ended Sunday. The finding was somewhat surprising since a recent increase in precipitation in some key wheat-growing areas had led many traders to expect an overall improvement in the crop. Corn futures prices were slightly lower in early trading, due in part to slack export demand. Slow foreign demand also limited early gains in the soybean market, but higher cash prices and strengthening chart signals provided a generally bullish tone. Cautious trading was expected ahead of the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s monthly grain supply-and-demand report, which was due out after the close today. In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 5 -RCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in May at $ 3.97 -LCB- a bushel; corn was \ cent lower to \ cent higher with May at $ 2.66 \ a bushel; oats were unchanged to -RCB- cent lower with May at $ 1.86 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 1 cent higher with May at $ 7.20 a bushel Livestock futures were mixed while pork bellies were slightly lower in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .17 cent to .47 cent lower with April at 77.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .23 cent higher with April at 77.30 cents a pound; hogs were .07 cent lower to .25 cent higher with April at 39.80 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .17 cent to .30 cent lower with