<HEAD>Budget Writers Look at Military, Domestic Spending</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 7 grafs new on today's meetings; picks up 5th graf pvs,
The revenues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 White House and congressional budget writers, with deadlines slipping away, pushed today to finish their talks on a compromise spending and tax package for next year. `` We're hoping to come to an agreement but we have n't made it,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, the senior <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, as he entered today's meeting. `` When we get one issue resolved, we run into another,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.M. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> counterpart, who said he was still optimistic. The bargainers have been meeting behind closed doors for more than a month in search of a compromise plan for reducing the federal deficit to $ 100 billion next year, as required by the Gramm-Rudman law. Several of the group's own, informal deadlines for actions have passed. With some more significant ones looming, including <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' April 15 deadline for passing a budget resolution, the negotiators were pressing to finish today. A budget pact would be formally announced at a White House meeting. But without agreement today that was unlikely until next week because President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is leaving town. Based on latest estimates and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s $ 1.16 trillion spending plan, about $ 28 billion in deficit reduction is required. The group has agreed that about half would come from spending restraints and half from raising revenues. The revenues include roughly $ 3.4 billion from selling government assets, $ 5.2 billion from raising various fees for government services and some $ 5.6 billion would be in unspecified new taxes _ but presumably none that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would concede violate his campaign promise for no new taxes. More than $ 7 billion in savings would be made by restraining entitlement programs _ those requiring direct benefit payments to individuals _ including more than $ 2.5 billion trimmed from the expected growth in Medicare costs. Monday's session was dedicated to deciding generally where cuts in non-entitlement government programs would be made, at the Pentagon and at domestic agencies, according to participants who spoke on the condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed that military spending be allowed to grow with inflation, while domestic programs _ other than his own initiatives _ would be frozen at the previous year's levels. Democrats in the talks have proposed trimming back defense growth so that more domestic demands can be met. The bargainers traded offers Monday toward a possible compromise on those and on the small but also politically sensitive foreign aid budget. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has personally contacted at least one lawmaker to lobby against cuts in foreign aid _ a program now administered by his old friend, Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, who appeared before the negotiators early in the talks. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has a self-imposed April 15 deadline for producing a budget resolution and even if agreement is reached quickly, that deadline will be missed by weeks. Even if the negotiators complete their task this week, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget committees must draft more detailed spending plans for each chamber to consider. Then, the two chambers would need to approve a single, compromise plan. The budget, which does not require the president's signature, serves as the guide for annual spending bills and tax legislation for the new fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1. If <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the president do n't by then bring down the deficit to within $ 10 billion of the $ 100 billion goal, the administration is required under the Gramm-Rudman law to order across-the-board spending cuts to make up the difference.
</TEXT>
