charges and claims the plant is safe. <PERSON> Ordonez </PERSON> said an out-of-court settlement was `` not out of the picture.'' `` Our concern now is to develop alternate sources of energy,'' he said. `` If that can be met, the money aspect can be minimized. What is important is that we get something for the same value which would help us solve our power needs.'' A <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> source said the remarks were hypothetical. Philippine and <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> officials held lengthy negotiations before the decision to file the suit. <PERSON> Ordonez </PERSON> was interviewed after <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s estranged vice president, called on the administration to operate the plant because of the country's power shortage <PERSON> Ordonez </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said they did not understand <ORGANIZATION> Laurel </ORGANIZATION>'s position because the vice president voted with the cabinet in 1986 to close the plant Laurel quit as foreign secretary in 1987 and joined the political opposition last year. `` According to our lawyers, we have sufficient evidence in the matter of proving that we got a raw deal from <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION>,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said Monday. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pugliese </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> executive vice president, said in a statement released in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> that the company was willing `` to explore how we can help bring the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> nuclear power plant into service.'' `` We are confident we built a safe plant,'' he said. `` Prior to its mothballing by the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> government, it had passed every official inspection of its readiness to load, fuel and begin startup testing.'' In <LOCATION> Ne