 The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> cut its global export quota by 351,000 bags Tuesday to shore up falling prices. The cut in the October 1988-September 1989 quota was triggered automatically by a fall in the average coffee price below $ 1.15 a pound. One bag equals 132 pounds. The coffee organization's 15-day composite indicator for Monday, calculated on Tuesday, dropped to $ 1.1498 from $ 1.1523 on Friday. The organization, made up of coffee producer and consumer nations, has set a target price for coffee of $ 1.20 - $ 1.40 In February, it twice cut the global export quota when the average price fell below $ 1.20 a pound. The three cuts affect only the quotas of countries producing the poorer grade robusta beans, principally the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. The organization wants to boost supplies of the prized arabica beans grown throughout <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Only if the price of arabica falls from its current level of $ 1.40 a pound to under $ 1.30 will arabica producers face a reduction in their export quotas. The robusta producers affected by Tuesday's cut, with the size of the reduction in parentheses, are <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION> -LRB- 38,500 bags -RRB-, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> -LRB- 78,000 -RRB-, <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> -LRB- 101,500 -RRB-, <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION> -LRB- 20,000 -RRB-, <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> -LRB- 13,000 -RRB-, <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION> -LRB- 67,000 -RRB- and <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> -LRB- 33,000 -RRB-.
