<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     04-11 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0175</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market rose in fairly quiet trading today with many investors cautious ahead of the barrage of economic data due out this week. The producer price index, which serves as a gauge of inflationary pressures, is scheduled for release on Friday along with reports on merchandise trade and industrial production. Analysts said recession-sensitive stocks like foods and soaps, which have shown steady gains in the last few weeks, continued to do well. A number of other sectors, including high technology, entertainment and toys, also performed surprisingly well despite the low volume, they said. Many analysts in the financial world believe economic growth has begun to slow since the start of the year. The employment report last Friday provided mixed signals about the economy. Although the jobless rate slid to 5 percent, fewer than 100,000 new jobs were created. Market participants are looking to the new data to provide a direction for the economy.
</TEXT>
