<HEAD>Democrats' Minimum Wage Plan Moves Ahead After Rejection of Bush
Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 5 grafs to raise reference to $4.55 level, insert
reax from Mrs. Dole; PICKS UP graf 4 pvs, `More amendments...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> rejected President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s minimum wage plan Tuesday and moved closer to confronting him with legislation raising the hourly figure to $ 4.55, which he repeatedly has promised to veto. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, on a 61-39 vote largely along party lines, backed an amendment to legislation sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., that brought the measure essentially in line with a House-passed bill that would boost the minimum wage to $ 4.55 by October 1991 Rejected, by 58-41, was <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal to increase the minimum wage by 30 cents a year from the current $ 3.35 an hour to $ 4.25 in January 1992. It was the second time <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal was defeated in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rejected it three weeks ago. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s action brought a quick response from the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. `` Today <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had a golden opportunity,'' Labor Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said after the vote. `` But <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democrats squandered the chance, the first chance in eight years, to raise the minimum wage.'' More amendments were being considered before the legislation faced a final <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote, likely to come Wednesday, but no further significant changes were expected before then. `` We compromised,'' said <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, referring to his past proposals to raise the minimum wage even higher. He also noted a number of other changes in the legislation, including expanded exemptions for small businesses, to meet Republican concerns. `` The president's approach is a far superior approach,'' Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, said in his unsuccessful effort to win support for substituting <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal for the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> bill. The action seemed to guarantee the first domestic-policy showdown between <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, barring a compromise while the bill is before a conference committee that will work out minor differences between the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> versions. Such a deal, however, appears unlikely. `` There is n't going to be a compromise,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. `` It's going to be $ 4.25 an hour and a six-month training wage, period.'' Democrats nonetheless called on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to accept their proposal. `` If there is any one thing that the 101st <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must do it is to increase the minimum wage,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, chastising <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for opposing a $ 4.55 an hour minimum wage while supporting expanded capital gains tax breaks for the wealthy. `` This legislation will be a test of whether we indeed are seeking a kindler, gentler nation,'' said <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>. Both the defeated <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposal and the amended <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> bill contain provisions allowing some workers to be paid a wage below the federal minimum wage. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has insisted that provision extend for six months to all newly hired workers, regardless of prior work experience. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, like the sponsors of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill, balked at that proposal but to win the support of moderate and conservative Democrats agreed on a two-month period during which some employees could be paid 85 percent of the minimum wage. That provision was contained in the amendment, offered by Democratic Sens. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>. `` Our training wage proposal is a proper balance of the need to train new workers and the need to set a fair minimum wage,'' said <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>. The Graham-Pryor amendment requires an employee to hold one job for at least 30 days before the two-month training period would expire. The House-passed bill also allows for a two-month training period at a subminimum wage but only if the affected employee had no prior job experience.
