<HEAD>Judge: Diamond Shamrock Insurer Liable For Agent Orange</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A state judge has ruled that insurance companies do n't have to pay for a $ 25 million dioxin cleanup at the site of a former Diamond Shamrock plant, but must fund payments to <ORGANIZATION> Agent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> victims, insurance company attorneys said Tuesday. The case centers around dioxin produced as a byproduct of herbicides, including Agent Orange, made at a <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> plant between 1951 and 1969 by the old <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alkali </ORGANIZATION> company, a predecessor to <LOCATION> Shamrock </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Diamond </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> has restructured and now is called <ORGANIZATION> Maxus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The company sued more than 100 insurers seeking coverage for the cleanup of the dioxin, which is linked to certain cancers, liver disease and a severe skin rash known as chloracne. In a decision released to lawyers on Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Morristown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, ruled that <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION>'s actions removed it from coverage, said <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> heard a non-jury trial that began in September. The decision could have wide-ranging effects in other cases in which companies seek to have their insurers handle millions of dollars in chemical and toxic waste cleanups, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bates </PERSON>, who represents <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Re-Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. The opinion was to be filed Wednesday morning. Insurance company attorneys provided excerpts from it, but <PERSON> Diamond </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> lawyers could not be reached for comment. <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON>, reached at home, confirmed his ruling but declined to discuss it, referring questions to the written opinion. `` Even by the standards of the 1951 to 1969 period, <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION>'s conduct in operating the <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> plant was unacceptably wrong and irresponsible,'' <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> wrote `` Diamond always put its narrowly perceived economic interest first. It deliberately and persistently cheated on the limited environmental regulations which were in place.'' But <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> also found that the insurance companies have to pay the bulk of <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 23 million share of a $ 180 million settlement reached in 1984 between makers of Agent Orange used in the Vietnam War and those who sued over its health effects. <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> interpreted the company's insurance contracts to mean that the insurers would have to bear most of the Agent Orange payments, and established how the payments would be distributed among the carriers, according to <PERSON> Bates </PERSON>. Lawyers for the company could not be reached. They either had gone home for the evening or did not return phone calls. A <ORGANIZATION> Maxus </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, Ginger Shearburn, could not be reached. There was no answer at the company and she did not return a telephone call left on her home answering machine.
