<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Northrop Named in Indictment on Cruise Missile Guidance System</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details of indictments, statement from
Bonner; no pickup. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and five current and former employees were indicted Tuesday on charges they conspired to defraud the government in building components for the guidance system for the cruise missile and the Harrier jet fighter. The 167-count indictment announced by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON> charged that <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> and the five conspired to install install parts of the cruise missile system which failed to meet government specifications. The indictment also alleged that lengthy reliability testing on the cruise missile's Flight Data Transmitter was not performed as required and that three of the defendants supervised false testing and falsification of test results. If convicted on all charges, <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> faces a maximum fine of more than $ 30 million. Each of the individual defendants would face maximum jail sentences of five years on each count and fines ranging from $ 5,000 to $ 250,000. `` Today's indictment is part of our continuing efforts to identify, prosecute and hopefully deter defense procurement fraud,'' <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON> said in a statement. He said the indictment was the result of a two-year probe by a multiagency task force. There was no immediate reaction to the indictment from <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>. `` Obviously we have n't seen it, so we ca n't comment,'' said <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Waskul </PERSON>, a spokesman at the Century City office. Named in the indictment were <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamron </PERSON>, a resident of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and vice president and general manager of the Precision Products Divsion of <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>. Also named were <PERSON> Leopold </PERSON> <PERSON> Engler </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, formerly a vice president with <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonsalves </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Glendora </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, former manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> department of <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hannan </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Glendora </LOCATION>, formerly quality assurance supervisor for <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> of <PERSON> Yorba </PERSON> <PERSON> Linda </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, former chief engineer for <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. With regard to the Harrier jet project, the indictment accused <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>, Gonzalves, <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Hannan </PERSON> of conspiring to defraud the government about the stabilization systems sold by <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> to be installed in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> jet. The indictment accused the defendants of failing to conduct vibration tests at levels required by the contract on sensor assemblies used in the jet, and then falsely certifying they had been properly tested. The Harrier can take off from short fields and can hover, and sophisticated stability controls are critical to its performance and safety. On the cruise missile project, the indictment charges that <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Yamron </PERSON> and <PERSON> Engler </PERSON> knew that the Flight Data Transmitter was required to withstand temperatures as low as -65 degrees, but supplied parts that froze at temperatures of -40 to -50 degrees. Many of the cruise missile's presumed targets are deep within the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where temperatures can drop to extreme levels. Should the Flight Data Transmitter fail in extreme cold, the weapon could not reach its target. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> produced and shipped approximately 1,175 Flight Data Transmitters between 1981 and 1989 for use in the missile, which have been deployed on B-52 and B-1B bombers. The company produced and shipped 189 sensor assemblies for the Harrier jet between 1982 and 1989. <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> are now evaluating the evidence on the alleged falsifications in order to determine if action must be taken to ensure the reliability of the missiles and the Harrier. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> also is the target of five civil lawsuits by former employees who alleged the company falsified test results and cheated the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on the MX missile project. In addition to well-publicized battles with critics of the MX program, the company faces a congressional investigation of allegations of improper payments to South Korean businessmen in an unsuccessful effort to sell its F-20 Tigershark fighter in that country in 1984. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> is also the main contractor for the B-2 stealth bomber.
